dom 8 in \u6771\u4eac\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0|accessdate=2014-01-04|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/otherppvs/article_75461.shtml|title=Caldwell's NJPW Tokyo Dome results 1/4: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of New Japan's biggest show of the year - four title changes, former WWE/TNA stars featured, more|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=2014-01-04|accessdate=2014-01-04|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Okada's eighth successful title defense took place on February 11 at [[The New Beginning in Osaka (2014)|The New Beginning in Osaka]], where he defeated Hirooki Goto.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=811|title=The New Beginning in Osaka|accessdate=2014-02-11|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222022825/http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=811|archivedate=2014-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/misc-news/46739-2-11-njpw-ippv-results-osaka-japan-okada-goto|title=2/11 NJPW iPPV Results: Osaka, Japan (Okada/Goto)|last=Namako|first=Jason|date=2014-02-12|accessdate=2014-02-13|work=Wrestleview}}</ref> On April 6 at [[Invasion Attack 2014]], Okada found himself a new challenger in [[Bullet Club]]'s newest member, the debuting [[A.J. Styles]], who claimed that Okada was still the same \"young boy\" (rookie) he had known in TNA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result_game.php?e=827&c=6216|title=Invasion Attack 2014|accessdate=2014-04-06|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407085723/http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result_game.php?e=827&c=6216|archivedate=2014-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/otherppvs/article_77512.shtml|title=Caldwell's NJPW PPV results 4/6: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of \"Invasion Attack 2014\" - Nakamura regains IC Title, A.J. Styles big angle, new NWA tag champions, more|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=2014-04-06|accessdate=2014-04-06|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On May 3 at [[Wrestling Dontaku 2014]], Okada's thirteen-month reign as the IWGP Heavyweight Champion came to an end, when he lost the title to Styles in his ninth defense, after Yujiro Takahashi turned on him and Chaos and joined Bullet Club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=838|script-title=ja:\u30ec\u30b9\u30ea\u30f3\u30b0\u3069\u3093\u305f\u304f 2014|accessdate=2014-05-03|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508074949/http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=838|archivedate=2014-05-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/misc-news/48292-aj-styles-crowned-the-new-iwgp-heavyweight-champion|title=AJ Styles crowned the new IWGP Heavyweight Champion|last=Namako|first=Jason|date=2014-05-03|accessdate=2014-05-03|work=Wrestleview}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/262979/|script-title=ja:\uff21\uff2a\u3000\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u6975\u60aa\u846c\u3000\uff29\uff37\uff27\uff30\u738b\u5ea7\u975e\u9053\u6234\u51a0|date=2014-05-04|accessdate=2014-05-04|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kazuchika Okada at BCW East meets West.jpg|thumb|upright|Okada in May 2014]]\nIn May, Okada took part in NJPW's North American tour, during which he received a rematch for the IWGP Heavyweight Championship. On May 17 at [[War of the Worlds (2014 wrestling)|War of the Worlds]] in New York City, Okada unsuccessfully challenged Styles for the title in a three-way match, which also included [[Michael Elgin]], whom Styles pinned for the win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/otherppvs/article_78455.shtml|title=Caldwell's ROH iPPV results 5/17: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of War of the Worlds - ROH Title & IWGP Title main events, new ROH tag champs, Steen vs. Nakamura, more|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=2014-05-17|accessdate=2014-05-17|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Okada received another shot at the title on May 25 at [[Back to the Yokohama Arena]], but was again defeated by Styles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=842|title=Back to the Yokohama Arena|accessdate=2014-05-25|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/otherppvs/article_78619.shtml|title=Caldwell's NJPW iPPV results 5/25: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of live show featuring Styles vs. Okada for IWGP World Title, MOTY Contender, NWA Tag Titles, more|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=2014-05-25|accessdate=2014-05-25|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> From July 21 to August 8, Okada took part in the [[2014 G1 Climax]], where he won his block with a record of eight wins and two losses, which included a win over Styles,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/otherppvs/article_79706.shtml|title=Caldwell's NJPW G1 Climax results 7/21 (Night 1): Complete coverage of A.J. Styles vs. Okada main event, Tanahashi, Nakamura, Shelton Benjamin, Bullet Club, more|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=2014-07-21|accessdate=2014-08-08|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> advancing to the finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=871 |script-title=ja:\u30d0\u30c7\u30a3\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30c8Presents G1 Climax 24|accessdate=2014-08-08|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812065927/http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=871|archivedate=2014-08-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/misc-news/50055-8-8-njpw-g-1-climax-day-11-recap-okada-suzuki|title=8/8 NJPW G-1 Climax Day 11 recap (Okada/Suzuki)|last=Namako|first=Jason|date=2014-08-08|accessdate=2014-08-08|work=Wrestleview}}</ref> On August 10, Okada defeated Chaos stablemate Shinsuke Nakamura to win the 2014 G1 Climax.<ref name=G1Climax2014Finals>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=872|script-title=ja:\u30d0\u30c7\u30a3\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30c8Presents G1 Climax 24|accessdate=2014-08-10|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812223238/http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=872|archivedate=2014-08-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/otherppvs/article_80097.shtml|title=Caldwell's New Japan G1 Climax finals results 8/10: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of Okada vs. Nakamura tournament finals, Styles vs. Tanahashi, Jeff Jarrett, ROH tag champs, more|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=2014-08-10|accessdate=2014-08-10|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On September 21 at [[Destruction in Kobe (2014)|Destruction in Kobe]], Okada teamed with Yoshi-Hashi to unsuccessfully challenge Bullet Club's [[Drew Hankinson|Doc Gallows]] and Karl Anderson for the IWGP Tag Team Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=886|title=Destruction in Kobe|accessdate=2014-09-21|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924040927/http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=886|archivedate=2014-09-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/otherppvs/article_80838.shtml|title=Caldwell's New Japan PPV results 9/21: Complete live coverage of \"Destruction in Kobe\" - Nakamura regains IC Title, Tanahashi vs. Shibata, A.J. Styles, new Jr. Hvt. champion, more|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=2014-09-21|accessdate=2014-09-21|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Two days later at [[Destruction in Okayama (2014)|Destruction in Okayama]], Okada successfully defended his IWGP Heavyweight Championship number one contender's contract against Karl Anderson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=888|title=Destruction in Okayama|accessdate=2014-09-23|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/misc-news/50879-9-23-njpw-results-okayama-japan-okada-anderson|title=9/23 NJPW Results: Okayama, Japan (Okada/Anderson)|last=Namako|first=Jason|date=2014-09-23|accessdate=2014-10-13|work=Wrestleview}}</ref> On October 13 at [[King of Pro-Wrestling (2014)|King of Pro-Wrestling]], Okada made another successful defense of his contract against Tetsuya Naito.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=889|title=King of Pro-Wrestling|accessdate=2014-10-13|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017231408/http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=889|archivedate=2014-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/otherppvs/article_81243.shtml|title=PPV results - 10/13 New Japan in Tokyo, Japan: Styles drops IWGP World Hvt. Title to Tanahashi, more title changes, former WWE star returns to New Japan, more|date=2014-10-13|accessdate=2014-10-13|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> The following month, Okada once again teamed up with Yoshi-Hashi for the [[2014 World Tag League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=12707|script-title=ja:\u300eWorld Tag League 2014\u300f\u51fa\u5834\u30c1\u30fc\u30e0\uff06\u516c\u5f0f\u6226\u304c\u6c7a\u5b9a\uff01 \u68da\u6a4b\u306f\u30e8\u30b7\u30bf\u30c4\u3068\u30bf\u30c3\u30b0\u7d50\u6210\uff01 \u685c\u5ead\u3001AJ\u3001\u67f4\u7530\u3001ROH\u3001NWA\u3082\u53c2\u6226!|date=2014-11-11|accessdate=2014-12-05|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112222204/http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=12707|archivedate=2014-11-12}}</ref> The team finished their block with a record of four wins and three losses, failing to advance to the finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=912|title=World Tag League 2014|accessdate=2014-12-05|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210130824/http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=912|archivedate=2014-12-10}}</ref> On January 4, 2015, at [[Wrestle Kingdom 9 in Tokyo Dome]], Okada received his shot at the IWGP Heavyweight Championship, but was defeated by the defending champion, Hiroshi Tanahashi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=902|script-title=ja:Wrestle Kingdom 9 in \u6771\u4eac\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0|accessdate=2015-01-04|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104154549/http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=902|archivedate=2015-01-04}}</ref><ref name=WK9PWT>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/otherppvs/article_82579.shtml|title=Caldwell's NJPW Tokyo Dome show results 1/4: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of live Wrestle Kingdom PPV - Tanahashi vs. Okada, Bullet Club, Nakamura, Jim Ross, more|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=2015-01-04|accessdate=2015-01-04|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Okada then started a stoyline, where the loss to Tanahashi had broken him both physically and mentally, causing him to enter a [[Slump (sports)|slump]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/356507/|script-title=ja:\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u201c\uff11\u30fb\uff14\u30b7\u30e7\u30c3\u30af\u201d\u3067\u6df1\u523b\u30b9\u30e9\u30f3\u30d7|date=2015-01-15|accessdate=2015-03-05|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> This led to a rivalry between him and Bullet Club's [[Bad Luck Fale]], who scored several pinfall wins over Okada, including in the first round of the [[2015 New Japan Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result_game.php?e=937&c=7133|title=New Japan Cup 2015|accessdate=2015-03-05|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/374444/|script-title=ja:\u3010\u65b0\u65e5\uff2e\uff2a\uff23\u3011\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u521d\u6226\u6557\u9000\u2026\u3084\u3063\u3071\u308a\u30b9\u30e9\u30f3\u30d7\uff1f|date=2015-03-06|accessdate=2015-03-06|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> Okada finally defeated Fale in a singles match on April 5 at [[Invasion Attack 2015]], after which he announced his intention of regaining the IWGP Heavyweight Championship by attacking A.J. Styles at the conclusion of the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=956 |title=Invasion Attack 2015 |accessdate=2015-04-05 |work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] |language=Japanese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409000342/http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=956 |archivedate=2015-04-09 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Arena_Reports_10/article_84294.shtml|title=Show results - 4/5 NJPW \"Invasion Attack\" in Tokyo, Japan: A.J. Styles defends IWGP World Title in main event, ROH tag teams win both Tag Titles, Bullet Club in action, more|date=2015-04-05|accessdate=2015-04-05|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kazuchika Okada 2015.JPG|thumb|left|Okada celebrating after capturing the [[IWGP Heavyweight Championship]] for the third time in July 2015]]\nOn July 5 at [[Dominion 7.5 in Osaka-jo Hall]], Okada defeated Styles to win the IWGP Heavyweight Championship for the third time.<ref name=Dominion75>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=990 |title=Dominion 7.5 in Osaka-jo Hall |accessdate=2015-07-05 |work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] |language=Japanese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706044456/http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=990 |archivedate=2015-07-06 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/more/more-top-stories/102-japan/43407-new-japan-dominion-live-coverage-from-osaka-jo-hall-styles-vs-okada-for-iwgp-title-nakamura-vs-goto-for-ic-title-and-notes-on-biggest-event-since-the-tokyo-dome|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150919041705/http://www.f4wonline.com/more/more-top-stories/102-japan/43407-new-japan-dominion-live-coverage-from-osaka-jo-hall-styles-vs-okada-for-iwgp-title-nakamura-vs-goto-for-ic-title-and-notes-on-biggest-event-since-the-tokyo-dome|title=New Japan Dominion live coverage from Osaka Jo Hall - Styles vs. Okada for IWGP title, Nakamura vs. Goto for IC title and notes on biggest event since the Tokyo Dome, plus all G-1 main events|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|archivedate=2015-09-19|date=2015-07-04|accessdate=2015-07-05|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> From July 23 to August 15, Okada took part in the [[2015 G1 Climax]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/component/content/article/80-features-and-tv-reviews/43611-the-big-audio-nightmares-guide-to-the-annual-new-japan-g1-climax|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722020322/http://www.f4wonline.com/component/content/article/80-features-and-tv-reviews/43611-the-big-audio-nightmares-guide-to-the-annual-new-japan-g1-climax|title=The Big Audio Nightmare's Guide to the annual New Japan G1 Climax|last=Sempervive|first=Mike|archivedate=2015-07-22|date=2015-07-18|accessdate=2015-08-15|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> He entered the final day with a chance to advance from his block, but a loss against Chaos stablemate Shinsuke Nakamura cost him a spot in the finals, giving him a record of seven wins and two losses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=1011|script-title=ja:\u30d0\u30c7\u30a3\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30c8Presents G1 Climax 25|accessdate=2015-08-15|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> On August 16, Okada had a staredown with [[Genichiro Tenryu]], who chose him to be his opponent in his retirement match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/436310/|script-title=ja:\uff11\uff11\u30fb\uff11\uff15\u5929\u9f8d\u5f15\u9000\u8a66\u5408\u3067\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u6226\u201c\u6c7a\u5b9a\u201d|date=2015-08-17|accessdate=2015-08-17|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> On November 15 at [[Tenryu Project#Genichiro Tenryu Retirement ~ Revolution Final|Revolution Final]], Okada defeated Tenryu in his retirement match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daily.co.jp/newsflash/ring/2015/11/15/0008569089.shtml|script-title=ja:\u5929\u9f8d\u304c\u5f15\u9000\u8a66\u5408\u3067\u51c4\u7d76\u8ca0\u3051\u300c\u8ca0\u3051\u305f\u3041\u300d|date=2015-11-15|accessdate=2015-11-15|work=Daily Sports Online|publisher=[[Kobe Shimbun]]|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/index.php/2015/11/15/1115-tenryu-retirement-in-tokyo-japan-tenryu-vs-okada-funk-hansen-appear-more/|title=11/15 Tenryu Retirement in Tokyo, Japan: Tenryu vs. Okada, Funk & Hansen appear, more|date=2015-11-15|accessdate=2015-11-15|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On December 7, Okada won his third MVP award from ''Tokyo Sports'', while his match with Tenryu was named the Match of the Year.<ref name=TokyoSports2015Awards>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/481078/|script-title=ja:\u3010\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u5927\u8cde\u3011\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u30fb\u30ab\u30ba\u30c1\u30ab\u304c\uff13\u5ea6\u76ee\u306e\uff2d\uff36\uff30\u3000\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\u30d0\u30a6\u30c8\u3082\u53d7\u8cde\u3057\uff12\u51a0\u9054\u6210|date=2015-12-08|accessdate=2015-12-08|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=15411|script-title=ja:\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u30fb\u30ab\u30ba\u30c1\u30ab\u304c2015\u5e74\u5ea6\u300c\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u5927\u8cde\u300dMVP\uff01 \u5929\u9f8d\u6226\u3067\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\u30d0\u30a6\u30c8\u3082\u7372\u5f97\uff01 \u6765\u5e74\u306e\u62b1\u8ca0\u306f\u300c\u7d50\u5a5a\u3057\u305f\u3044\u300d!? \u672c\u9593\u670b\u6643\u304c\u6280\u80fd\u8cde\u7372\u5f97\uff01|date=2015-12-08|accessdate=2015-12-08|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> With the win, Okada became only the fifth three-time MVP award winner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/kazuchika-okada-won-tokyo-sports-2015-mvp-award-203216|title=Kazuchika Okada won Tokyo Sports 2015 MVP Award|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=2015-12-07|accessdate=2015-12-08|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> In December 2015, Okada signed a one-year contract extension with NJPW. However, following A.J. Styles and Shinsuke Nakamura's departures from the promotion the following month, NJPW owner [[Takaaki Kidani]] announced that the promotion was scrapping the one-year contract system and was looking to offer Okada, their top priority, a new five-year \u00a5200 million contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/505620/|script-title=ja:\u65b0\u65e5\u304c\u201c\u81f3\u5b9d\u201d\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u6d41\u51fa\u963b\u6b62\u3078\uff12\u5104\u5186\u30d7\u30ed\u30b8\u30a7\u30af\u30c8|date=February 13, 2016|accessdate=February 13, 2016|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> On January 4, 2016, Okada defeated 2015 G1 Climax winner Hiroshi Tanahashi in the main event of [[Wrestle Kingdom 10 in Tokyo Dome]] to retain the IWGP Heavyweight Championship and become the new ace of the promotion, the match at that time was the longest in the history of the [[January 4 Dome Show]] .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/wrestle-kingdom-10-live-results-kazuchika-okada-vs-hiroshi-tanahashi-204791|title=Wrestle Kingdom 10 live results: Kazuchika Okada vs Hiroshi Tanahashi|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=2016-01-03|accessdate=2016-01-04|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref>\n\n====Longest-reigning IWGP Heavyweight Champion (2016\u20132018)====\n[[File:Kazuchika Okada IWGP Heavyweight champion 2016.png|thumb|upright|Okada as the [[IWGP Heavyweight Champion]] in February 2016]]\nOkada made his third successful title defense on February 11 at [[The New Beginning in Osaka (2016)|The New Beginning in Osaka]] against Hirooki Goto.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-beginnings-live-results-iwgp-heavyweight-championship-kazuchika-okada-vs-hirooki-goto|title=NJPW Beginnings live results: IWGP Heavyweight championship Kazuchika Okada vs Hirooki Goto|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=2016-02-11|accessdate=2016-02-11|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> On April 10 at [[Invasion Attack 2016]], Okada lost the IWGP Heavyweight Championship to [[2016 New Japan Cup]] winner Tetsuya Naito, following outside interference from Naito's ''[[Los Ingobernables de Japon]]'' stablemates [[Tetsuya Bushi|Bushi]], [[Takaaki Watanabe|Evil]] and the debuting [[Seiya Sanada|Sanada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-invasion-attack-live-results-kazuchika-okada-vs-tetsuya-naito-iwgp-championship-210736|title=NJPW Invasion Attack live results: Kazuchika Okada vs. Tetsuya Naito for the IWGP Championship|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=2016-04-09|accessdate=2016-04-10|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> Okada gained revenge on Sanada by defeating him on May 3 at [[Wrestling Dontaku 2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=1123|script-title=ja:\u30ec\u30b9\u30ea\u30f3\u30b0\u3069\u3093\u305f\u304f 2016|accessdate=2016-05-03|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> This led to a rematch with Naito on June 19 at [[Dominion 6.19 in Osaka-jo Hall]], where Okada won the IWGP Heavyweight Championship for the fourth time.<ref name=Dominion619>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-dominion-live-results-tetsuya-naito-vs-kazuchika-okada-iwgp-hw-championship-214876|title=NJPW Dominion live results: Tetsuya Naito vs Kazuchika Okada for the IWGP HW Championship|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=2016-06-18|accessdate=2016-06-19|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daily.co.jp/ring/2016/06/20/0009204052.shtml|script-title=ja:\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\uff14\u5ea6\u76ee\uff29\uff37\uff27\uff30\u738b\u5ea7\u596a\u53d6|date=2016-06-20|accessdate=2016-06-20|work=Daily Sports Online|publisher=[[Kobe Shimbun]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> From July 18 to August 12, Okada took part in the [[2016 G1 Climax]], where he finished tied second in his block with a record of five wins, one draw and three losses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/g1climax2016/|title=2016 New Japan G1 Climax Results|accessdate=2016-08-12|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> A 30-minute time limit draw against Hiroshi Tanahashi on the final day eliminated both men from advancing to the finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-g1-climax-26-night-17-results-kazuchika-okada-vs-hiroshi-tanahashi-218536|title=NJPW G1 Climax 26 night 17 results: Kazuchika Okada vs. Hiroshi Tanahashi|last=Rose|first=Bryan|date=2016-08-12|accessdate=2016-08-12|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> During the G1 Climax, Okada was defeated by Pro Wrestling Noah representative [[Naomichi Marufuji]], which led to his first title defense following the tournament on October 10 at [[King of Pro-Wrestling (2016)|King of Pro-Wrestling]], where Okada retained the IWGP Heavyweight Championship against Marufuji, thus setting up the main event of [[Wrestle Kingdom 11 in Tokyo Dome]] between Okada and the 2016 G1 Climax winner [[Kenny Omega]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-king-pro-wrestling-live-results-kazuchika-okada-vs-naomichi-marufuji-222396|title=NJPW King of Pro Wrestling live results: Kazuchika Okada vs. Naomichi Marufuji|last=Rose|first=Bryan|date=2016-10-09|accessdate=2016-10-10|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> On December 14, Okada became the second wrestler to win three consecutive Match of the Year awards from ''Tokyo Sports'' for his 2016 G1 Climax opener against Naomichi Marufuji.<ref name=TSBestBout2016>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/628687/|script-title=ja:\u3010\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u5927\u8cde\u3011\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\u30d0\u30a6\u30c8\u3000\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u306f\u6238\u60d1\u3044\u300c\u80f8\u3092\u5f35\u3063\u3066\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\u30d0\u30a6\u30c8\u3068\u8a00\u3048\u308b\u8a66\u5408\u3067\u306f\u2026\u300d|date=2016-12-14|accessdate=2016-12-14|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nOn January 4, 2017, Okada successfully defended the IWGP Heavyweight Championship against Kenny Omega at Wrestle Kingdom 11 in Tokyo Dome.<ref name=WrestleKingdom11>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-wrestle-kingdom-11-live-results-kazuchika-okada-vs-kenny-omega-227626|title=NJPW Wrestle Kingdom 11 live results: Kazuchika Okada vs. Kenny Omega|last1=Rose|first1=Bryan|last2=Currier|first2=Joseph|date=2017-01-03|accessdate=2017-01-04|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> At 46 minutes and 45 seconds, the match is the longest in the history of the [[January 4 Tokyo Dome Show]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/636006/|script-title=ja:\u3010\u65b0\u65e5\uff11\u30fb\uff14\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0\u3011\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u3000\u53f2\u4e0a\u6700\u9577\uff14\uff16\u5206\uff14\uff15\u79d2\u306e\u6b7b\u95d8\u5236\u3057\uff29\uff37\uff27\uff30\uff12\u5ea6\u76ee\u306e\u9632\u885b\uff01|date=2017-01-05|accessdate=2017-01-05|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> Wrestling journalist [[Dave Meltzer]], in his ''[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]'', gave the match a six-star rating. He added that Okada and Omega \"may have put on the greatest match in pro wrestling history\" and that it was the best match he had ever seen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://members.f4wonline.com/wrestling-observer-newsletter/january-9-2017-wrestling-observer-newsletter-ronda-rousey-loses|title=January 9, 2017 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: Ronda Rousey loses potential final fight, NJPW Wrestle Kingdom 11 review|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=2017-01-05|accessdate=2017-01-05|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The match was also praised by the likes of [[Daniel Bryan]], [[Mick Foley]] and [[Stone Cold Steve Austin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/wwe/story/wwe-john-cena-kenny-omega-royal-rumble-hint-instagram-010817|title=John Cena trolls wrestling fans worldwide on his Instagram|last=Schwartz|first=Nick|date=2017-01-08|accessdate=2017-01-27|work=[[Fox Sports]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metronews.ca/news/winnipeg/2017/01/20/transcona-pro-wrestler-kenny-omega-greatest-match.html|title=Winnipeg wrestler Kenny Omega wins 'greatest match in pro wrestling history'|last=Allen|first=Taylor|date=2017-01-23|accessdate=2017-01-27|work=Metro Winnipeg|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126224704/http://www.metronews.ca/news/winnipeg/2017/01/20/transcona-pro-wrestler-kenny-omega-greatest-match.html|archive-date=2017-01-26|url-status=dead}}</ref> The day after Wrestle Kingdom 11, Okada and Chaos were attacked by the returning Minoru Suzuki and his Suzuki-gun stable,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-new-years-dash-results-return-suzuki-gun-227721|title=NJPW New Year's Dash results: The return of Suzuki-gun|last=Rose|first=Bryan|date=2017-01-05|accessdate=2017-02-05|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> which led to his third title defense on February 5 at [[The New Beginning in Sapporo (2017)|The New Beginning in Sapporo]], where he defeated Suzuki.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-new-beginning-sapporo-live-results-okada-vs-suzuki-229561|title=NJPW New Beginning in Sapporo live results: Okada vs. Suzuki|last1=Meltzer|first1=Dave|authorlink1=Dave Meltzer|last2=Currier|first2=Joseph|date=2017-02-04|accessdate=2017-02-05|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/648448/|script-title=ja:\u3010\u65b0\u65e5\u672c\u3011\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u6fc0\u95d8\uff14\uff10\u5206\u8d85\u3000\u30a2\u30e2\u30fc\u30ec\u306b\u6367\u3052\u308b\uff29\uff37\uff27\uff30\u738b\u5ea7\uff36\uff13|date=2017-02-06|accessdate=2017-02-06|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> Okada's fourth defense took place on April 9 at [[Sakura Genesis 2017]], where he defeated [[2017 New Japan Cup]] winner [[Katsuyori Shibata]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-sakura-genesis-live-results-okada-vs-shibata-233351|title=NJPW Sakura Genesis live results: Okada vs. Shibata|last=Rose|first=Bryan|date=2017-04-08|accessdate=2017-04-09|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/672964/|script-title=ja:\u3010\u65b0\u65e5\u672c\u3011\uff29\uff37\uff27\uff30 \uff36\uff14\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0 \u76ee\u6307\u3059\u306f\uff11\u30fb\uff14\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0\u5730\u4e0a\u6ce2\u30b4\u30fc\u30eb\u30c7\u30f3\u653e\u9001|date=2017-04-10|accessdate=2017-04-10|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> Okada's fifth defense took place on May 3 at [[Wrestling Dontaku 2017]], where he defeated Bad Luck Fale. After the match, Okada nominated Omega as his next challenger for the championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-wrestling-dontaku-live-results-okada-faces-bad-luck-fale-234786|title=NJPW Wrestling Dontaku live results: Okada faces Bad Luck Fale|last=Rose|first=Bryan|date=2017-05-02|accessdate=2017-05-03|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/681682/|script-title=ja:\uff29\uff37\uff27\uff30\u738b\u5ea7\uff36\uff15\u306e\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u3000\u30b1\u30ac\u4eba\u7d9a\u304d\u306e\u65b0\u65e5\u306b\u7dca\u6025\u63d0\u8a00|date=2017-05-04|accessdate=2017-05-03|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> The rematch between Okada and Omega on June 11 at [[Dominion 6.11 in Osaka-jo Hall]] ended in NJPW's first 60-minute time limit draw in 12 years, meaning that Okada was successful in his sixth defense.<ref name=Dominion611>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-dominion-live-results-kazuchika-okada-vs-kenny-omega-237066|title=NJPW Dominion live results: Kazuchika Okada vs. Kenny Omega|last=Rose|first=Bryan|date=2017-06-10|accessdate=2017-06-11|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/696024/|script-title=ja:\u3010\u65b0\u65e5\u30fb\u5927\u962a\u3011\uff29\uff37\uff27\uff30\u738b\u8005\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u3000\u30b1\u30cb\u30fc\u76f8\u624b\u306b\u30d5\u30eb\u30bf\u30a4\u30e0\u30c9\u30ed\u30fc\u9632\u885b\u300c\u6700\u9ad8\u306e\uff16\uff10\u5206\u3067\u3057\u305f\u300d|date=2017-06-12|accessdate=2017-06-12|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> Okada's seventh title defense took place during the first night of [[G1 Special in USA]] on July 1, where he defeated [[Cody Rhodes|Cody]].<ref name=G1SpecialN1>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/07/01/radicans-71-njpw-g1-special-usa-night-1-report-tournament-begins-crown-first-iwgp-u-s-champion-okada-defends-iwgp-hvt-championship-cody-rhodes/|title=Radican's 7/1 NJPW G1 Special In USA (night 1) report \u2013 tournament begins to crown first IWGP U.S. Champion, Okada defends IWGP Hvt. Championship against Cody (Rhodes)|last=Radican|first=Sean|date=2017-07-01|accessdate=2017-07-01|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/704321/|script-title=ja:\u3010\u65b0\u65e5\uff2c\uff21\u3011\uff29\uff37\uff27\uff30\u738b\u8005\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u304c\uff23\uff4f\uff44\uff59\u4e0b\u3057\uff36\uff17\u3000\u56e3\u4f53\u521d\u306e\u7c73\u56fd\u30d3\u30c3\u30b0\u30de\u30c3\u30c1\u3067\u5b58\u5728\u611f|date=2017-07-02|accessdate=2017-07-02|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> Okada then entered the [[2017 G1 Climax]], where he finished with a record of six wins, one draw and two losses,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/08/12/2017-new-japan-g1-climax-results/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813060704/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/08/12/2017-new-japan-g1-climax-results/|title=2017 New Japan G1 Climax Standings, Results, Viewing Guide|archivedate=2017-08-13|date=2017-08-12|accessdate=2017-08-13|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> failing to advance to the finals due to losing to Kenny Omega in their third match against each other on August 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-g1-climax-27-b-block-finals-live-results-okada-vs-omega-iii-240836|title=NJPW G1 Climax 27 B Block finals live results: Okada vs. Omega III|last=Rose|first=Bryan|date=2017-08-12|accessdate=2017-08-12|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> On October 9 at [[King of Pro-Wrestling (2017)|King of Pro-Wrestling]], Okada avenged a loss suffered during the 2017 G1 Climax by making his eighth successful title defense against Evil, setting him up against G1 Climax winner Tetsuya Naito in the main event of [[Wrestle Kingdom 12]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-king-pro-wrestling-live-results-kazuchika-okada-vs-evil-244191|title=NJPW King of Pro Wrestling live results: Kazuchika Okada vs. Evil|last=Rose|first=Bryan|date=2017-10-08|accessdate=2017-10-09|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/791104/|script-title=ja:\u3010\u65b0\u65e5\u3011\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u304c\uff29\uff37\uff27\uff30\u738b\u5ea7\uff36\uff18\u3000\uff11\u30fb\uff14\u6771\u4eac\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0\u3067\u5185\u85e4\u3068\u6fc0\u7a81\u3078|date=2017-10-10|accessdate=2017-10-10|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nOn October 22, Okada became the longest-reigning IWGP Heavyweight Champion in history by breaking the previous record of 489 days, held by [[Shinya Hashimoto]]. On January 3, 2018, Okada also broke Hiroshi Tanahashi's record of 1,358 combined days as champion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/japan-news/new-japan/92366-kazuchika-okada-officially-becomes-longest-reigning-iwgp-champion-in-history/|title=Kazuchika Okada becomes the longest-reigning IWGP Champion|last=Namako|first=Jason|date=2017-10-22|accessdate=2017-10-23|work=Wrestleview}}</ref> The following day at Wrestle Kingdom 12, Okada defeated Tetsuya Naito to retain the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-wrestle-kingdom-12-live-results-okada-naito-omega-jericho-249171|title=NJPW Wrestle Kingdom 12 live results: Okada-Naito, Omega-Jericho|last1=Renner|first1=Ethan|last2=Currier|first2=Joseph|date=2018-01-03|accessdate=2018-01-04|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> On February 10 at [[The New Beginning in Osaka (2018)|The New Beginning in Osaka]], Okada defeated Sanada to retain the championship for the tenth time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-new-beginning-osaka-live-results-okada-vs-sanada-251491|title=NJPW NEW BEGINNING IN OSAKA LIVE RESULTS: OKADA VS. SANADA|last=Renner|first=Ethan|date=2018-02-10|accessdate=2018-09-07|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> On March 21, Okada was challenged for the title by [[New Japan Cup#2018|New Japan Cup]] winner [[Zack Sabre Jr.]] and at [[Sakura Genesis 2018|Sakura Genesis]] went on to defeat Sabre Jr. to tie Hiroshi Tanahashi's record for most successful title defenses in one reign at 11 defenses. After the match, Okada would be confronted by Tanahashi, indicating a future match for the title. They would meet at [[Wrestling Dontaku 2018]], where Okada would defeat Tanahashi for his record-breaking 12th successful title defense,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/20888?showResult=1|title=HAMAKATSU Presents WRESTLING DONTAKU 2018 \u2013 05.04 {{!}} NEW JAPAN PRO-WRESTLING|last=NJPW|website=NJPW|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-09}}</ref> breaking Tanahashi's record of 11, and earning a 5 1/2 Star rating from Wrestling Observer Newsletter. His next challenger was then revealed to be Kenny Omega, having been chosen due to Okada's frustration with having one win, draw, and loss against him. In their fourth match, they competed in a two out of three falls match at [[Dominion 6.9 in Osaka-jo Hall]] (with no time limit to ensure there is no possibility of a draw as in their second singles match at [[Dominion 6.11 in Osaka-jo Hall|Dominion 6.11]]), where Omega would defeat Okada 2\u20131 to win the championship after a 65 minute match, ending Okada\u2019s record-breaking championship reign at 720 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/22417?showResult=1|title=2018.06.09 \u2013 DOMINION 6.9 in OSAKA-JO HALL {{!}} NEW JAPAN PRO-WRESTLING|last=NJPW|website=NJPW|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-09}}</ref>\n\n====Gedo's betrayal and feud with Jay White (2018\u2013present)====\nOkada then entered the 2018 G1 Climax, where he finished with a record of six wins, one draw and two losses, exactly the same as the previous year's event, failing to advance to the finals.<ref name=\"g1climax18\">{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-new-years-dash-results-return-suzuki-gun-227721|title=NJPW G1 CLIMAX 28 NIGHT 17 LIVE RESULTS: OKADA VS. TANAHASHI|last=Rose|first=Bryan|date=2018-08-10|accessdate=2018-09-07|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> The event saw a change of image for Okada following the defeat by Omega, with his hair dyed red and portraying an indifferent attitude.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/07/15/radicans-7-14-g1-climax-28-night-1-report-a-block-action-kicks-off-the-tournament-updated-standings-viewing-guide/|title=RADICAN\u2019S 7/14 G1 Climax 28: Night 1 report \u2013 A block action kicks off the tournament, updated standings, viewing guide|last=Radican|first=Sean|date=2018-07-15|accessdate=2018-09-07|work=[[Pro Wrestling Torch]]}}</ref> This caused him to lose his first two matches against [[Jay White (wrestler)|Jay White]] and Bad Luck Fale,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/24743?showResult=1|title=2018.07.14 G1 CLIMAX 28 Night01 {{!}} NEW JAPAN PRO-WRESTLING|accessdate=2018-08-02|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/24745?showResult=1|title=2018.07.16 G1 CLIMAX 28 Night03 {{!}} NEW JAPAN PRO-WRESTLING|accessdate=2018-07-16|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=English}}</ref> although he would go on to the win the rest of the matches in his block, until the last one; another 30-minute time limit draw against Tanahashi.<ref name=\"g1climax18\"/> At the 2018 G1 Climax Finals, Okada parted ways with his longtime manager Gedo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/japan/post-njpw-g1-climax-28-notes-future-matches-okada-gedo-263651|title=POST-NJPW G1 CLIMAX 28 NOTES: FUTURE MATCHES, OKADA & GEDO|last=Rose|first=Bryan|date=2018-08-12|accessdate=2018-09-07|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> Unsatisfied by their draw in the G1, Tanahashi opted to defend the contract for his [[Wrestle Kingdom 13]] title shot against Okada. On September 23 at Destruction in Kobe, Okada was defeated by Tanahashi. Afterwards, he was attacked by Jay White before Gedo, his former manager, came out seemingly to stop him, only to betray Okada by hitting him in the back with a chair.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wrestlinginc.com/wi/news/2018/0923/646088/njpw-destruction-in-kobe-results/|title=NJPW Destruction In Kobe Results: Okada Vs. Tanahashi, CHAOS Fractures, Jr. Heavyweight Title Tourny - Wrestling Inc.|work=Wrestling Inc.|access-date=2018-09-24|language=en}}</ref> This led to a match between White and Okada at Wrestle Kingdom 13, where he was defeated. In March, Okada competed in the New Japan Cup. He would defeat Michael Elgin in Round 1, and fellow Chaos members [[Mikey Nicholls]], Will Ospreay, and Tomohiro Ishii in Round 2, the Quarterfinals, and Semi-Finals, respectively. He would go on to defeat Sanada in the finals of the tournament and win his second New Japan Cup. In doing so, he won the opportunity to challenge Jay White at New Japan/Ring of Honor joint show, [[G1 Supercard]], for the IWGP Heavyweight Championship.<ref name=\"NJCup19\">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=24.03.2019 New Japan Cup Finals|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/40410?showResult=1|publisher=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|access-date=March 24, 2019}}</ref> At the event on April 6, Okada defeated White to win the title for the fifth time.<ref>{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=4/6 ROH and NJPW G1 Supercard results: Powell\u2019s live review of Jay White vs. Kazuchika Okada for the IWGP Hvt. Championship, Jay Lethal vs. Matt Taven vs. Marty Scurll in a three-way ladder match for the ROH Title, Tetsuya Naito vs. Kota Ibushi for the IWGP Intercontinental Championship, and more|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/04/06/4-6-roh-and-njpw-g1-supercard-results-powells-live-review-of-jay-white-vs-kazuchika-okada-for-the-iwgp-hvt-championship-jay-lethal-vs-matt-taven-vs-marty-scurll-in-a-three-way-ladder-match-for/|publisher=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|access-date=April 6, 2019}}</ref> Okada then would successfully defend his title against Sanada on the second night of the [[Wrestling Dontaku 2019]] event.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/43044?showResult=1|title=05.04.19 Wrestling Dontaku 2019 Night 2|publisher=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref> Then, Okada would successfully defend his title against [[Chris Jericho]] at [[Dominion 6.9 in Osaka-jo Hall (2019)|Dominion 6.9]] for his second title defense.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/46521?showResult=1 |title=DOMINION 6.9 in OSAKA-JO HALL |publisher=New Japan Pro-Wrestling  |access-date=June 9, 2019}}</ref> At [[NJPW Royal Quest|Royal Quest]], Okada would successfully defeat [[Minoru Suzuki]] for his third title defence, subsequently going on retain the title again at [[King of Pro-Wrestling (2019)|King of Pro Wrestling]] vs [[Sanada (wrestler)|Sanada]] which would set up a title match with [[G1 Climax 29|G1 Climax]] winner [[Kota Ibushi]] at [[Wrestle Kingdom 14]]. On the first night of the two-day event, Okada would retain the Championship against Ibushi, enabling him to advance to the Double Gold Dash Title-For-Title Match on Night 2, where Okada's fifth reign was ended by [[IWGP Intercontinental Championship|IWGP Intercontinental Champion]] [[Tetsuya Naito]]. Okada would then enter into a feud with [[Taichi]], where at [[The New Beginning in Sapporo]] night 2, Okada would defeat Taichi. Okada was then announced to be facing Jay White in the first round of the New Japan Cup 2020, however due to the [[19-20 Coronavirus Pandemic]] all New Japan Cup and further New Japan events were cancelled.\n\n=== Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre (2018) ===\nOn August 17, 2018, Okada with [[Negro Casas]] and [[\u00daltimo Guerrero]] defeated [[Diamante Azul]], [[Valiente (wrestler)|Valiente]] and [[M\u00edstico II|M\u00edstico]] in [[Arena M\u00e9xico]].<ref>http://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/2018/08/18/okada-se-presento-en-la-arena-mexico-con-una-victoria?internal_source=PLAYLIST</ref>\n\n==Other media==\nAlong with fellow NJPW wrestler Shinsuke Nakamura, Okada is featured in the Japanese music video for [[Pharrell Williams]]' song ''[[Happy (Pharrell Williams song)|Happy]]'', released in May 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=11486|script-title=ja:\u3042\u306e\u30d5\u30a1\u30ec\u30eb\u30fb\u30a6\u30a3\u30ea\u30a2\u30e0\u30b9\u306e\u5927\u30d2\u30c3\u30c8\u30b7\u30f3\u30b0\u30eb\u300e\u30cf\u30c3\u30d4\u30fc\u300f\u65e5\u672c\u7248\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30af\u30d3\u30c7\u30aa\u306b\u3001\u4e2d\u9091\u771f\u8f14\uff06\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u30fb\u30ab\u30ba\u30c1\u30ab\u304c\u51fa\u6f14\uff01|date=2014-04-30|accessdate=2014-04-30|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> In 2015, Okada voiced a character in the ''[[World Trigger]]'' anime series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanspo.com/geino/news/20150330/geo15033005030005-n1.html|script-title=ja:\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u30fb\u30ab\u30ba\u30c1\u30ab\u3001\u300c\u30ef\u30fc\u30eb\u30c9\u30c8\u30ea\u30ac\u30fc\u300d\u3067\u58f0\u512a\u306b\u521d\u6311\u6226|date=2015-03-30|accessdate=2015-04-05|work=[[Sankei Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> The following year, he voiced a character in another anime, ''Future Card Buddy Fight 100''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/498390/|script-title=ja:\uff29\uff37\uff27\uff30\u738b\u8005\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\uff12\u5ea6\u76ee\u306e\u58f0\u512a\u6311\u6226\u300c\u304b\u306a\u308a\u7dca\u5f35\u3057\u305f\u300d|date=2016-01-25|accessdate=2016-01-25|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> Okada, along with fellow NJPW wrestlers Hiroshi Tanahashi, [[Hiroyoshi Tenzan]], Satoshi Kojima, Tetsuya Naito and Toru Yano, appears as a member of the gang Justis in the 2016 video game ''[[Yakuza 6: The Song of Life]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=17380|script-title=ja:\u65b0\u65e5\u672c\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u30ea\u30f3\u30b0\u306e\u4eba\u6c17\u9078\u624b\u304c\u795e\u5ba4\u753a\u6700\u5927\u306e\u30ae\u30e3\u30f3\u30b0\u306b\uff1f\uff01\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u3001\u68da\u6a4b\u3001\u5185\u85e4\u30896\u9078\u624b\u304cPlayStation\u00ae4\u5c02\u7528\u30bd\u30d5\u30c8\u300e\u9f8d\u304c\u5982\u304f\uff16 \u547d\u306e\u8a69\u3002\u300f\u306b\u51fa\u6f14\u6c7a\u5b9a\uff01|date=2016-09-16|accessdate=2016-09-16|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> In January 2017, it was announced that the ''[[Tekken 7: Fated Retribution]]'' video game would feature Okada's in-ring costume as an alternate outfit for the character [[King (Tekken)|King]]. When equipped, King performs Okada's finishing maneuver, the ''Rainmaker'', as his \"Rage Art\" move.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/78933|script-title=ja:\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u306e\u4e16\u754c\u3067\u30ec\u30a4\u30f3\u30e1\u30fc\u30ab\u30fc\u304c\u70b8\u88c2!! \u30d5\u30a1\u30f3\u6ce8\u76ee\u306e\u30b3\u30e9\u30dc\u4f01\u753b\u304c\u76ee\u767d\u62bc\u3057!!\u3010\u300c\u9244\u62f37FR\u300d\u30b3\u30e9\u30dc\u767a\u8868\u4f1a\u898b\u3011|date=2017-01-03|accessdate=2017-01-03|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> The Okada-geared King was featured on the September 12, 2017 episode of WWE's ''[[WWE 205 Live|205 Live]]'' program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-results/wwe-205-live-results-jack-gallagher-aligns-brian-kendrick-242736|title=WWE 205 Live results: Jack Gallagher aligns with Brian Kendrick|last=Peeples|first=Jeremy|date=2017-09-12|accessdate=2017-09-13|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref>\n\nOkada played rhythm guitar on several tracks on The High Crusade's [[extended play]] ''Main Statement'', which was released on January 20, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/fakekinkade/status/1219445865594617856|title=So this is super special to me: my band, The High Crusade, posted our long lost EP that was buried for years. Main Statement also sees @rainmakerXokada play rhythm guitar on a couple different tracks. Seriously. This may not be a big announcement to some, but to me, massive.|website=Twitter|first=Alex|last=Shelley|authorlink=Alex Shelley|date=January 20, 2020|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}<br>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/fakekinkade/status/1219446533256613889|title=You can download it for free, too. Hear Kazuchika shred ... Bet no one knew @rainmakerXokada could play power chords, but here we are. Thank you, @SuperChrisSabin and @iPeteyWilliams. Bros.|website=Twitter|first=Alex|last=Shelley|authorlink=Alex Shelley|date=January 20, 2020|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOkada was engaged to [[TV Asahi]] presenter Yoko Mori, whom he had been in a relationship with from 2013 to 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/640947/|script-title=ja:\u65b0\u65e5\u30fb\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u3068\u30c6\u30ec\u671d\u30fb\u68ee\u8449\u5b50\u30a2\u30ca\u7d50\u5a5a\u3078\uff01\uff12\uff10\uff11\uff13\u5e74\u304b\u3089\u771f\u5263\u4ea4\u969b|date=2017-01-16|accessdate=2017-01-16|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> In August 2014, after his uncle and cousin had both been diagnosed with cancer, Okada established the \"Rainmaker Kikin\" (\"Rainmaker Fund\") to battle children's cancer. For every match Okada won, he pledged to donate \u00a530,000 (the equivalent of US$277.20).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=12203|script-title=ja:\u3010G124\u3011\u300c\u6771\u30b9\u30dd\u300d8\u670812\u65e5\u53f7\u306e\u88cf\u4e00\u9762\u306b\u300eG1\u300f\u3092\u5236\u3057\u305f\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u30fb\u30ab\u30ba\u30c1\u30ab\u306e\u8a18\u4e8b\u304c\u63b2\u8f09!! \u30ec\u30a4\u30f3\u30e1\u30fc\u30ab\u30fc\u57fa\u91d1\u8a2d\u7acb!!|date=2014-08-12|accessdate=2014-08-12|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/299852/2/|script-title=ja:G\uff11\u8987\u8005\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0 \u304c\u3093\u306e\u5b50\u4f9b\u305f\u3061\u306e\u305f\u3081\u300c\u30ec\u30a4\u30f3\u30e1\u30fc\u30ab\u30fc\u57fa\u91d1\u300d\u8a2d\u7acb\u3078|date=2014-08-12|accessdate=2014-08-12|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, voice actress [[Suzuko Mimori]] announced her marriage to Okada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2019/04/12-1/voice-actress-suzuko-mimori-marries-pro-wrestler-kazuchika-okada|title=Voice Actress Suzuko Mimori Marries Pro-Wrestler Kazuchika Okada|last=Chapman|first=Paul|date=2019-04-12|website=[[Crunchyroll]]|language=en-us|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n[[File:\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u30fb\u30ab\u30ba\u30c1\u30ab.jpg|thumb|upright|Okada as the [[IWGP Heavyweight Champion]] in July 2013]]\n*'''[[CBS Sports]]'''\n**Match of the Year (2018) {{small|vs. [[Kenny Omega]] at [[Dominion 6.9 in Osaka-jo Hall|Dominion 6.9]]}}<ref name=\"CBSSportsAwards2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/the-man-comes-around-becky-lynch-breaks-out-for-wwe-as-the-2018-wrestler-of-the-year/|title=The Man comes around: Becky Lynch breaks out for WWE as the 2018 Wrestler of the Year|last=Silverstein|first=Adam|date=December 26, 2018|work=[[CBS Sports]]}}</ref>\n*'''[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]'''\n**[[IWGP Heavyweight Championship]] ([[IWGP Heavyweight Championship#Title history|5 times]])<ref name=NJPW/>\n**[[G1 Climax]] ([[G1 Climax#2012|2012]], [[G1 Climax#2014|2014]])<ref name=NJPW/>\n**[[New Japan Cup]] ([[New Japan Cup#2013|2013]], [[New Japan Cup#2019|2019]])<ref name=NJPW032313/><ref name=\"NJCup19\"/>\n**Best Bout (2017) {{small|vs. [[Kenny Omega]] on June 11}}<ref>{{cite AV media|date=December 19, 2017 |title=\u30aa\u30ea\u30b8\u30ca\u30eb \u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc 2017\u5e7412\u670819\u65e5 \u3082\u3046\u3059\u3050\u30a4\u30c3\u30c6\u30f3\u30e8\u30f3\uff01\u65b0\u65e5\u672c\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u5927\u5fd8\u5e74\u4f1a\uff01|language=Japanese |url=https://njpwworld.com/p/o_original_0008_288|website=njpwworld.com|publisher=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|time=00:57:56}}</ref>\n*'''''[[Nikkan Sports]]'''''\n**MVP Award (2012, 2013, 2015, 2017)<ref name= NIKKAN2012>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/wrestlingscout/home/updates/nikkansportsawards-2012|title=Nikkan Sports Awards - 2012|website= wrestlingscout |date=September 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nikkansports.com/battle/news/p-bt-tp0-20131226-1236087.html|script-title=ja:\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u300c\u5f53\u