\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Okada, Kazuchika}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chaos (professional wrestling) members]]\n[[Category:IWGP Heavyweight champions]]\n[[Category:Japanese expatriates in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Japanese male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:People from Anj\u014d]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Aichi Prefecture]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Japanese professional wrestler}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name=Kazuchika Okada\n|image=Kazuchika Okada 2016.JPG\n|caption=Okada in February 2016\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1987|11|08}}\n|birth_place=[[Anj\u014d, Aichi]], Japan\n|spouse ={{marriage|[[Suzuko Mimori]]|2019}}\n|names='''Kazuchika Okada'''<br>Okato<br>Dragon George<ref>https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/37139?showCards=1</ref>\n|height={{height|m=1.90}}<ref name=NJPW/><ref name=Central>{{cite web|url=http://www.puroresucentral.com/okada.html|title=Kazuchika Okada|accessdate=2010-01-25|work=Puroresu Central}}</ref>\n|weight={{convert|107|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<ref name=NJPW/><ref name=NikkanSports>{{cite web|url=http://www.nikkansports.com/battle/news/p-bt-tp0-20120205-899471.html|script-title=ja:\u65b0\u30a8\u30fc\u30b924\u6b73\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\uff29\uff37\uff27\uff30\u6311\u6226\uff0f\u65b0\u65e5\u672c|date=2012-02-05|accessdate=2012-11-20|work=[[Nikkan Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n|billed=[[Tokyo]], Japan<ref name=TNA>{{cite web|url=http://www.impactwrestling.com/roster/Wrestler-Roster/item/2774-Okada|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928035310/http://www.impactwrestling.com/roster/Wrestler-Roster/item/2774-Okada|title=Okada|archivedate=2011-09-28|accessdate=2011-06-21|work=[[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]]}}</ref> \n|trainer=[[\u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=13945|script-title=ja:\u300e\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u306e\u90e8\u5c4b\u300f\u30a6\u30eb\u30c6\u30a3\u30e2\u30fb\u30c9\u30e9\u30b4\u30f3\u6821\u9577\u7de8\u30fb\u7b2c2\u56de! \u300c\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u307f\u305f\u3044\u306b\u300e\u30b3\u30a4\u30c4\u306f\u51fa\u4e16\u3059\u308b\u306a\u300f\u3063\u3066\u5f1f\u5b50\u306f\u508d\u306b\u7f6e\u3044\u3066\u307e\u3057\u305f\u300d|date=2015-05-08|accessdate=2015-05-08|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref><br>[[Yuji Nagata]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/420625/|script-title=ja:\u9b3c\u6559\u5b98\u5fa9\u6d3b\uff01\u6c38\u7530\u304c\uff27\uff11\u3067\u5143\u4ed8\u3051\u4eba\u306e\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u3092\u518d\u6559\u80b2|date=2015-07-11|accessdate=2015-07-11|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n|debut=August 29, 2004\n|retired=\n|}}\n{{nihongo|'''Kazuchika Okada'''|\u5ca1\u7530 \u548c\u7766|Okada Kazuchika|[[ring name]]: {{Nihongo2|\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u30fb\u30ab\u30ba\u30c1\u30ab}}}} (born November 8, 1987) is a Japanese [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]]. He is signed to [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW), where he is a five-time [[IWGP Heavyweight Championship|IWGP Heavyweight Champion]]. Okada's fourth reign with the championship is the longest in history at 720 days; he also holds the record for most successful title defenses with twelve.\n\nInitially trained by [[\u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n]] and making his debut in August 2004, Okada spent his first years in professional wrestling working in [[Mexico]], before returning to Japan and making NJPW his home promotion in mid-2007. Originally working as a [[Cruiserweight (professional wrestling)|junior heavyweight]], Okada graduated to the heavyweight division in April 2008, with limited success. In February 2010, NJPW sent Okada on a learning excursion to American promotion [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] (TNA), where he spent the next twenty months, mainly performing on the promotion's secondary television program, ''[[TNA Xplosion|Xplosion]]''. From January to March 2011, he performed under the name '''Okato''' on TNA's primary television program, ''[[Impact! (TV series)|Impact!]]'', as [[Samoa Joe]]'s sidekick in his rivalry with [[D'Angelo Dinero]].\n\nOkada's run with TNA ended in October 2011 and he returned to NJPW in January 2012, repackaged as {{nihongo|\"Rainmaker\"|\u30ec\u30a4\u30f3\u30e1\u30fc\u30ab\u30fc|Reinm\u0113k\u0101}}, complete with a new look and a [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous]] [[Gimmick (professional wrestling)|persona]]. Just a month later, Okada defeated [[Hiroshi Tanahashi]] to win NJPW's top title, the IWGP Heavyweight Championship, which he would hold for four months before losing it back to Tanahashi. The following August, Okada won NJPW's premier tournament, the [[G1 Climax]]. At the end of the year, the ''[[Tokyo Sports]]'' magazine named Okada the 2012 [[Tokyo Sports Puroresu Awards#MVP Award|MVP]] in all of Japanese professional wrestling. The following year, Okada first won the [[New Japan Cup#2013|New Japan Cup]] in March and then regained the IWGP Heavyweight Championship from Tanahashi in April. After a thirteen-month reign, Okada lost the title in May 2014. Three months later, he won his second G1 Climax. Okada has since won the IWGP Heavyweight Championship three more times and headlined NJPW's biggest annual event\u2014the [[January 4 Tokyo Dome Show]]\u2014six times including ([[Wrestle Kingdom 7 in Tokyo Dome|2013]], [[Wrestle Kingdom 9|2015]], [[Wrestle Kingdom 10|2016]], [[Wrestle Kingdom 11|2017]], [[Wrestle Kingdom 12|2018]] and [[Wrestle Kingdom 14|2020]]).\n\nIn 2017, Okada became the first Japanese wrestler to top ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]''{{'}}s [[Pro Wrestling Illustrated#PWI 500|list of the top 500 wrestlers in the world]]. His matches against [[Kenny Omega]] at [[Wrestle Kingdom 11]], [[Dominion 6.11 in Osaka-jo Hall]] and [[Dominion 6.9 in Osaka-jo Hall]] (all for NJPW's IWGP Heavyweight Championship), as well as the semi-finals of the 2017 [[G1 Climax]], earned a respective 6, 6\u00bc, 6, and 7 [[List of professional wrestling matches rated 5 or more stars by Dave Meltzer|stars]] from [[Dave Meltzer]] of the ''[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]''. The 7 star match is the highest star rating Meltzer has ever awarded.\n\n==Early life==\nOkada was born on November 8, 1987, in [[Anj\u014d, Aichi]].<ref name=NJPW>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/profile/721|script-title=ja:\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u30fb\u30ab\u30ba\u30c1\u30ab|accessdate=2017-06-28|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]}}</ref><ref name=NikkanSports/> As a child, he lived and attended a primary school in Anj\u014d. However, before completing primary school, Okada was lured by the nature in his mother's hometown in the [[Got\u014d Islands]] in [[Nagasaki Prefecture]] and chose to complete the rest of his primary education in a special boarding school there.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=\u30ec\u30b9\u30e9\u30fc\u30d2\u30e5\u30fc\u30de\u30f3\u30b9\u30c8\u30fc\u30ea\u30fcII \u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u30e9\u30fc\u7537\u306e\u5c65\u6b74\u66f8|last=|first=|publisher=\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9\u30dc\u30fc\u30eb\u30de\u30ac\u30b8\u30f3\u793e|year=2016|isbn=|location=Japan|pages=8\u201315}}</ref> Upon graduation, he returned to Anj\u014d.\n\nIn middle school, Okada joined the school's baseball and track team. Although he did not stand out as a baseball player, Okada was able to win first place in a regional 100 meter dash competition. His reputation as a sprinter was good enough to be scouted by high school recruiters.<ref name=\":0\" /> He was exposed to [[professional wrestling]] for the first time when one of his older brothers happened to borrow a [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW) video game from his friend.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n===Training and early career (2004\u20132007)===\nTrained by [[\u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n]] at his [[Toryumon (\u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n)|Toryumon]] [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#school|professional wrestling school]], Okada made his debut on August 29, 2004, against [[Negro Navarro]]<ref name=NJPW/><ref name=NikkanSports/> and would spend the next couple of years wrestling primarily in Toryumon Mexico.<ref name=Central/> In December 2005, Okada won the [[2005 Young Dragons Cup]].<ref name=NJPW/><ref name=PWHYoungDragons>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/mexico/toryumon/young.html#young2005|title=Young Dragons Cup 2005|accessdate=2015-05-08|work=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Okada would also make appearances in the United States and Canada for [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotions]] such as UWA Hardcore Wrestling and [[Chikara (professional wrestling)|Chikara]]. On October 27, 2006, Okada participated in UWA Hardcore Wrestling's 2006 Grand Prix Tournament, but was eliminated in the first round by [[T.J. Perkins|Puma]].<ref name=UWAHC>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/uwahardcore/|title=UWA Hardcore|accessdate=2012-02-13|work=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> The following day, Okada and \u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n unsuccessfully challenged [[Alex Shelley]] and [[Chris Sabin]] for the [[NWA International Lightweight Tag Team Championship]].<ref name=UWAHC/> On November 12, 2006, Okada made his debut for Chikara by defeating Osiris.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/chikara/|title=Chikara Pro Wrestling|accessdate=2012-02-13|work=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> During his time in UWA Hardcore Wrestling, Okada also unsuccessfully challenged Josh Prohibition for the UWA Canadian Championship on May 26, 2007.<ref name=UWAHC/> On July 22, 2007, Okada took part in \u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n's 20th anniversary show, where he wrestled in a [[six-man tag team match]] alongside NJPW wrestlers [[Jyushin Thunder Liger]] and [[Milano Collection A.T.]]<ref name=NJPW/> After the match, it was announced that Okada was graduating from Toryumon and joining NJPW.<ref name=NJPW/>\n\n===New Japan Pro-Wrestling (2007\u20132010)===\nUpon joining NJPW, Okada entered the [[NJPW Dojo]], where he went through further training.<ref name=CentralArchive>{{cite web|url=http://puroresucentral.com/okada.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128183737/http://puroresucentral.com/okada.html|title=Kazuchika Okada|archivedate=2010-11-28|accessdate=2015-05-08|work=Puroresu Central}}</ref> He would have a pre-debut match for the company on August 26, 2007, losing to [[Tetsuya Naito]].<ref name=CentralArchive/> A legitimate injury would sideline Okada for the next eight months and upon his return in April 2008 he would be billed as a heavyweight instead of a [[Cruiserweight (professional wrestling)|junior heavyweight]],<ref name=CentralArchive/> and have his official debut match on April 12, 2008, against [[Taichi Ishikari]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw.co.jp/profile/721|title=\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u30fb\u30ab\u30ba\u30c1\u30ab \uff5c \u65b0\u65e5\u672c\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u30ea\u30f3\u30b0|accessdate=2019-09-25|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> His career would start to pick up steam the following year with breakout performances in the NJPW vs. [[Pro Wrestling Noah]] war against the likes of [[Takashi Sugiura]] and [[Go Shiozaki]].<ref name=CentralArchive/> He would also wrestle [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#main eventer|main eventers]] such as [[Shinsuke Nakamura]], [[Hirooki Goto]] and [[Yoshihiro Tajiri|Tajiri]] and\u2014despite losing all of his big matches\u2014he was becoming a big crowd favorite.<ref name=CentralArchive/> In January 2010, NJPW announced that they would be sending Okada to [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] (TNA) for a developmental tour in order for him to become the wrestler NJPW believed he could be.<ref name=HeadingOverseas>{{cite web|url=http://www.puroresufan.com/njpw/?p=1353|title=Young warriors head overseas, ex-Noah stars on 1/31, Chono absent|date=2010-01-19|accessdate=2010-01-25|work=Strong Style Spirit}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1263930170 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130210071559/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1263930170 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-02-10 |title=New Japan star heading to TNA |date=2010-01-19 |last=Martin |first=Adam |accessdate=2011-12-20 |work=Wrestleview }}</ref> NJPW president Naoki Sugabayashi predicted the tour could take up to two or three years.<ref name=HeadingOverseas/> On January 31, 2010, Okada was defeated by former four-time [[IWGP Heavyweight Champion]] [[Hiroshi Tanahashi]] in his NJPW farewell match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.puroresufan.com/njpw/?p=1379|title=Results New Japan, 1/31/10|date=2010-01-31|accessdate=2010-01-31|work=Strong Style Spirit}}</ref>\n\n===Total Nonstop Action Wrestling (2010\u20132011)===\n[[File:Okada TNA Xplosion.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Okada at a ''[[TNA Xplosion]]'' taping in July 2010]]\nOkada made his TNA debut at the February 16, 2010, tapings of ''[[Impact! (TV series)|Impact!]]'', losing to Alex Shelley in a [[dark match]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwinsider.com/article/45171/tna-impact-spoilers-leading-into-the-live-monday-show-new-japan-star-debuts-and-more.html?p=1|title=TNA Impact spoilers leading into the live Monday show, New Japan star debuts and more|last=Wolfe|first=Dylan|date=2010-02-17|accessdate=2010-02-17|work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> At the March 9 tapings, Okada was defeated by [[Jay Lethal]] in another dark match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwinsider.com/article/45765/live-ongoing-tna-impact-spoilers-for-march-15.html?p=1|title=Complete spoilers for TNA Impact for March 15|last=Nichols|first=JP|date=2010-03-09|accessdate=2010-03-10|work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> On March 20, Okada made his debut for [[Jersey All Pro Wrestling]] (JAPW) at Wild Card VI, where he was defeated by fellow TNA wrestler [[Samoa Joe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2009/1269190722.php?style=dark|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604220057/http://www.wrestleview.com/news2009/1269190722.php?style=dark|title=Haas wins gold in New Jersey|last=Gerweck|first=Steve|archivedate=2011-06-04|date=2010-03-21|accessdate=2010-03-21|work=Wrestleview}}</ref> Okada's dark matches for TNA continued on March 23 with a loss against [[Christopher Daniels|Daniels]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwinsider.com/article/46160/ongoing-spoilers-from-orlando-for-march-29th-impact.html?p=1|title=Complete spoilers from Orlando for March 29th Impact|last=Nichols|first=JP|date=2010-03-23|accessdate=2010-03-24|work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> On April 6, Okada, using only his last name, competed in his first televised TNA match when he and [[Homicide (wrestler)|Homicide]] were defeated by [[The Young Bucks|Generation Me (Jeremy and Max Buck)]] in a [[tag team match]], which was later broadcast on the ''[[TNA Xplosion|Xplosion]]'' television program and the company's official website and [[YouTube]] channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwinsider.com/article/46541/complete-tna-impact-spoilers-from-next-weeks-last-episode-before-the-lockdown-ppv.html?p=1|title=Complete TNA Impact spoilers from next week's last episode before the Lockdown PPV|last=Toste|first=Dave|date=2010-04-07|accessdate=2010-04-07|work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TNA_News_1/article_40654.shtml|title=TNA News: This week's TNA Webmatch - solid tag match featuring Gen Me (Young Bucks) (w/video)|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=2010-04-14|accessdate=2010-04-15|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> That same week, Okada also began wrestling at TNA's [[House show|live events]].<ref name=HouseShow041010>{{cite web|url=http://wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1270996683|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413172741/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1270996683|title=4/10 TNA Results: Pikeville, KY|last=Martin|first=Adam|archivedate=2010-04-13|date=2010-04-11|accessdate=2010-04-14|work=Wrestleview}}</ref> On May 4, Okada and Homicide were defeated in another ''Xplosion'' match by [[Ink Inc.]] ([[Jesse Neal]] and [[Shannon Moore]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/47299/tna-impact-spoilers-for-thursday-return.html?p=1|title=TNA Impact spoilers for Thursday return|last=Johnson|first=Mike|date=2010-05-04|accessdate=2010-05-13|work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> On May 17, [[TNA X Division Championship|X Division Champion]] [[Doug Williams (wrestler)|Douglas Williams]] defeated Okada in a non-title ''Xplosion'' match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwinsider.com/article/47598/quick-spoiler-results-for-this-thursdays-impact.html?p=1|title=Quick spoiler results for this Thursday's Impact|last=Johnson|first=Mike|date=2010-05-17|accessdate=2010-05-18|work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> On July 15, Okada made his first appearance on ''Impact!'', running out to the ring in an attempt to stop former [[Extreme Championship Wrestling|ECW]] wrestlers from taking over the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1279001038 |title=Spoilers: TNA Impact for this Thursday |last=Martin |first=Adam |date=2010-07-13 |accessdate=2010-08-02 |work=Wrestleview |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428050636/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1279001038 |archivedate=2012-04-28 }}</ref> At the August 9 tapings, Okada picked up his first victory in TNA, defeating [[Kid Kash]] in a dark match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TNA_News_1/article_43008.shtml|title=TNA News: Spoilers - detailed Impact TV taping report for \"Whole F'n Show\" featuring new angle, MOTY candidate?, three title matches|first=Kevin|last=Tomich|date=2010-08-09|accessdate=2010-08-10|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On the October 8 ''Xplosion'', Okada formed a [[tag team]] with compatriot [[Akira Raijin|Kiyoshi]], but the two of them were then defeated in their first match together by Ink Inc.<ref>{{cite episode|title=TNA Xplosion ep. 315|episodelink=TNA Xplosion|series=TNA Xplosion|serieslink=TNA Xplosion|credits=[[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]]|network=[[Extreme Sports Channel]]|airdate=2010-10-08|season=|seriesno=|number=|minutes= approx. 28}}</ref> On the November 26 ''Xplosion'', Okada was defeated by [[Rob Terry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/news/161286|title=TNA Impact and Xplosion Taping Results (spoilers)|first=Chad|last=Webb|date=2010-11-09|accessdate=2010-11-27|work=411Mania}}</ref> On the December 17 ''Xplosion'', Okada was defeated by [[Stevie Richards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/news/162399|title=TNA Xplosion Taping Results (spoilers)|date=2010-11-16|accessdate=2010-12-22|last=Csonka|first=Larry|work=411Mania}}</ref> Okada and Kiyoshi had a rematch with Ink Inc. at the December 7 tapings of ''Xplosion'', but were once again defeated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1291837293|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101216170159/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1291837293|title=Spoilers: TNA Impact tapings for 12/16 and 1/6|archivedate=2010-12-16|date=2010-12-08|accessdate=2010-12-08|last=Martin|first=Adam|work=Wrestleview}}</ref>\n\nOn January 20, 2011, Okada turned into a [[Face (professional wrestling)|fan favorite]] as he made his second appearance on ''Impact!'', when he was revealed as the camera man whom Samoa Joe had hired to follow [[D'Angelo Dinero]] in order to expose his lies about helping the needy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_47015.shtml|title=Keller's TNA Impact report 1/20: Kurt Angle-Jeff Jarrett-Karen triangle saga continues, more They hype, RVD & Anderson vs. Beer Money|date=2011-01-23|last=Keller|first=Wade|authorlink=Wade Keller|accessdate=2011-02-04|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> During the appearance, Okada debuted a new look inspired by [[Kato (The Green Hornet)|Kato]] from ''[[The Green Hornet]]'' series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1296797269|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110205202942/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1296797269|title=Impact Results - 2/3/11|archivedate=2011-02-05|date=2011-02-04|last=Boutwell|first=Josh|accessdate=2011-02-13|work=Wrestleview}}</ref> Okada, now renamed Okato, made his first [[List of TNA pay-per-view events|TNA pay-per-view]] appearance at [[Against All Odds (2011)|Against All Odds]] on February 13, preventing Dinero from leaving the ring during his match with Joe. After losing the match, Dinero attacked both Okato and Joe.<ref name=AAO2011WON>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/content/view/19465/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110217000549/http://www.f4wonline.com/content/view/19465|title=TNA Against All Odds PPV report|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|archivedate=2011-02-17|date=2011-02-13|accessdate=2011-02-13|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnappvs/article_47702.shtml|title=Caldwell's TNA Against All Odds PPV results 2/13: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of live PPV - Anderson vs. Hardy, Genesis re-matches, fluid X Division situation|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=2011-02-13|accessdate=2011-02-13|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Okato made his ''Impact!'' in-ring debut on March 24, when he defeated Dinero via [[Professional wrestling#Disqualification|disqualification]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1301025665|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110409164540/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1301025665|title=Impact Results - 3/24/11|last=Boutwell|first=Josh|archivedate=2011-04-09|date=2011-03-25|accessdate=2011-03-25|work=Wrestleview}}</ref> The match concluded Okato's participation in the [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]] between Joe and Dinero and he subsequently returned to performing under his real surname. On the June 21 ''Xplosion'', Okada was defeated by Alex Shelley in the first round of the [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling tournaments#Xplosion Championship Challenge|Xplosion Championship Challenge]].<ref>{{cite episode|title=TNA Xplosion ep. 352|episodelink=TNA Xplosion|series=TNA Xplosion|serieslink=TNA Xplosion|credits=[[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]]|network=[[Challenge (TV channel)|Challenge]]|airdate=2011-06-21|season=|seriesno=|number=|minutes=}}</ref> On October 13, his profile was removed from TNA's roster page.\n\nTNA's handling of Okada was reportedly one of the reasons NJPW ceased the relationship between the two promotions shortly afterwards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/94917/tna-news-and-notes.html?p=1|title=TNA news and notes|last=Johnson|first=Mike|date=2015-07-06|accessdate=2015-07-06|work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/01/07/how-tna-factors-into-the-wwe-njpw-story/|title= How TNA factors into the WWE-NJPW story|last1=Radican|first1=Sean|last2=Caldwell|first2=James|date=2016-01-07|accessdate=2016-01-07|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref><ref name=SIExtra/> Despite not being used by TNA, Okada has stated that he felt that his time in the promotion was beneficial to him as he learned he needed more than just a good match''\u2014''he needed a [[Gimmick (professional wrestling)|character]]. According to Okada, in [[Japanese professional wrestling]] \"there is no character \u2013 it's fight, fight, fight\", but TNA's [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#agent|agents]] kept telling him that he needed a character, which led to him creating the \"Rainmaker\" persona upon his return to NJPW.<ref name=SIExtra/> In October 2017, it was reported that while representatives of the American promotion, now known as Impact Wrestling, were visiting Japan, attempting to revive the relationship between their company and NJPW, they specifically apologized to Okada for his treatment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=113261|title=Lots of Impact Wrestling updates heading into Bound for Glory|last=Johnson|first=Mike|date=2017-10-31|accessdate=2017-10-31|work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref>\n\n===Return to NJPW===\n====Sporadic appearances (2010\u20132011)====\nOn December 14, 2010, NJPW announced that Okada would be returning to the promotion on January 4, 2011, at [[Wrestle Kingdom V in Tokyo Dome]], where he would team with Hirooki Goto against Noah representatives Takashi Sugiura and [[Yoshihiro Takayama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=4830|script-title=ja:\u8c6a\u83ef\u7d62\u721b\u306a\u516813\u8a66\u5408\uff01 1\u67084\u65e5\u300c\u30ec\u30c3\u30b9\u30eb\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\u30c0\u30e0V in \u6771\u4eac\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0\u300d\u5bfe\u6226\u30ab\u30fc\u30c9\u6c7a\u5b9a\uff01|date=2010-12-14|accessdate= 2010-12-23|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.puroresufan.com/njpw/?p=2455|title=Full 1/4 Tokyo Dome card announced, plus 12/23 lineup!|date=2010-12-14|accessdate=2010-12-23|work=Strong Style Spirit}}</ref> On December 23, he made a surprise return to the promotion, performing a [[German suplex]] on Takayama, after a match where he and [[Minoru Suzuki]] had defeated [[Yuji Nagata]] and [[Wataru Inoue (wrestler)|Wataru Inoue]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.puroresufan.com/njpw/?p=2472|title=(Results) New Japan, 12/23/10|date=2010-12-23|accessdate=2010-12-23|work=Strong Style Spirit}}</ref> At Wrestle Kingdom V in Tokyo Dome, Takayama pinned Okada to win the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=132|script-title=ja:\u30ec\u30c3\u30b9\u30eb\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\u30c0\u30e0\u2164 \uff49\uff4e \u6771\u4eac\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|accessdate=2011-01-04|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1294158810|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107121731/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1294158810|title=1/4 TNA-NJPW Results: Tokyo, Japan|last=Gerweck|first=Steve|archivedate=2011-01-07|date=2011-01-04|accessdate=2011-01-04|work=Wrestleview}}</ref> After the event, Okada returned to the United States and TNA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.puroresufan.com/njpw/?p=2501|title=NJPW/CMLL cards announced, Tanahashi's first challenger to be determined on 1/30, Okada news|date=2011-01-05|accessdate=2011-01-08|work=Strong Style Spirit}}</ref> Okada returned to NJPW during the [[NJPW Invasion Tour 2011]] (NJPW's first tour of the United States) on May 13 in [[Rahway, New Jersey]], but was defeated by [[Montel Vontavious Porter|MVP]] in the first round of a [[IWGP Intercontinental Championship#Championship tournament|tournament]] to determine the inaugural [[IWGP Intercontinental Champion]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1305392240|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001054505/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1305392240|title=5/13 New Japan Pro-Wrestling Results: Rahway, NJ|last=Martin|first=Adam|archivedate=2012-10-01|date=2011-05-14|accessdate=2011-05-15|work=Wrestleview}}</ref> At the following day's event in [[New York City]], Okada teamed with [[Ryusuke Taguchi]] and [[Togi Makabe]] in a six-man tag team match, where they were defeated by [[Davey Richards]], Homicide and [[Rhino (wrestler)|Rhino]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1305481617|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522041320/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1305481617|title=5/14 New Japan Pro-Wrestling Results: New York|last=Martin|first=Adam|archivedate=2011-05-22|date=2011-05-15|accessdate=2011-05-15|work=Wrestleview}}</ref> On May 15, during the final day of the tour in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], Okada teamed with [[Charlie Haas]], Josh Daniels and [[Tiger Mask IV|Tiger Mask]] in an eight-man tag team match, where they were defeated by [[Chaos (professional wrestling)|Chaos]] (Shinsuke Nakamura, [[Gedo (wrestler)|Gedo]], [[Jado]] and [[Yujiro Takahashi]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1305557577|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610122633/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1305557577|title=5/15 New Japan Pro-Wrestling Results: Philly, PA|last=Martin|first=Adam|archivedate=2011-06-10|date=2011-05-16|accessdate=2011-05-16|work=Wrestleview}}</ref> On December 9, 2011, NJPW announced that Okada, having gained {{convert|11|kg|lb|abbr=on}} of muscle to increase his overall weight from {{convert|96|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<ref name=NJPWOld>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/data/detail_profile.php?f=376|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228010901/http://www.njpw.co.jp/data/detail_profile.php?f=376|script-title=ja:\u5ca1\u7530\u304b\u305a\u3061\u304b|archivedate=2010-12-28|accessdate=2010-12-23|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> to {{convert|107|kg|lb|abbr=on}},<ref name=NJPW/> would be returning to the promotion on January 4, 2012, at [[Wrestle Kingdom VI in Tokyo Dome]], where he would face [[Nobuo Yoshihashi|Yoshi-Hashi]], also making his return after a learning excursion to [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]] (CMLL).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=6765|script-title=ja:1.4\u6771\u4eac\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0\u3067\u3001\u6b66\u85e4\u656c\u53f8vs\u5185\u85e4\u54f2\u4e5f\u304c\u96fb\u6483\u6c7a\u5b9a! \u771f\u58c1vs\u9ad8\u5c71! MVP\u306e\u30d1\u30fc\u30c8\u30ca\u30fc\u306f\u30b7\u30a7\u30eb\u30c8\u30f3\u30fb\u30d9\u30f3\u30b8\u30e3\u30df\u30f3!!\u3000\u5168\u30ab\u30fc\u30c9\u6c7a\u5b9a!!|date=2011-12-09|accessdate=2011-12-09|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\n====Feud with Hiroshi Tanahashi (2012\u20132016)====\n[[File:RAIN MAKER OKADA.JPG|thumb|Okada in his Rainmaker pose in February 2012]]\nOn January 4, Okada defeated Yoshi-Hashi in his return match and then challenged Hiroshi Tanahashi to a match for the IWGP Heavyweight Championship following the show's main event.<ref name=WKVI>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=470|script-title=ja:NJPW 40th anniversary Tour. \u30ec\u30c3\u30b9\u30eb\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\u30c0\u30e0\u2165 in \u6771\u4eac\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0|accessdate=2012-01-04|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108044116/http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=470|archivedate=2012-01-08}}</ref> At the following day's press conference, where the title match was made official, Okada revealed that he had joined Chaos, NJPW's top [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous]] [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#stable|stable]], enlisting new stablemate Gedo as his [[Manager (professional wrestling)|manager]] and spokesperson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=6873|script-title=ja:\u300c\u9003\u3052\u3093\u306e\u304b\uff1f\u300d\u68da\u6a4b\u306b\u201c\u4fdd\u8b77\u8005\u201d\u5916\u9053\u304c\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u306e\u6311\u6226\u3092\u8feb\u308b!! \u4f1a\u898b\u52d5\u753b\uff061.4\u6771\u4eac\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0OP\u6620\u50cf\u3082\u30a2\u30c3\u30d7!!|date=2012-01-06|accessdate=2012-01-07|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> Adopting the new villainous persona of \"Rainmaker\", Okada changed the Japanese writing of his [[ring name]] from \"\u5ca1\u7530\u304b\u305a\u3061\u304b\" to \"\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u30fb\u30ab\u30ba\u30c1\u30ab\".<ref name=NJPW/><ref name=NikkanSports/><ref name=NJPWOld/> Okada described his new persona as a combination of the three professional wrestling styles he had learned, stating that he took his [[dropkick]] from Mexico, his \"fighting spirit\" from Japan and the \"TV and the entertainment\" from the United States.<ref name=SIExtra>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/extra-mustard/2016/05/11/trish-stratus-jimmy-hart-wwe-new-japan-kazuchika-okada|title=Week in Wrestling: Jimmy Hart on the art of theme songs; Trish Stratus|last=Barrasso|first=Justin|date=2016-05-11|accessdate=2016-08-11|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]}}</ref> In the month leading to the title match, Okada went on a main event win streak, which included pinning Tanahashi in a tag team match on January 29.<ref name=NJPW012912>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result_game.php?e=507&c=3766|title=NJPW 40th anniversary Tour New Japan Ism 2012|accessdate=2012-02-07|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result_game.php?e=508&c=3769|title=NJPW 40th anniversary Tour New Japan Ism 2012|accessdate=2012-02-07|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref name=NJIsm020412>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result_game.php?e=510&c=3775|title=NJPW 40th anniversary Tour New Japan Ism 2012|accessdate=2012-02-07|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> On February 12 at [[The New Beginning (2012)|The New Beginning]], Okada defeated Tanahashi to win the IWGP Heavyweight Championship for the first time.<ref name=NewBeginning>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=513|title=The New Beginning|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|accessdate=2012-02-12|language=Japanese}}</ref> Okada made his first title defense on March 4, defeating Tetsuya Naito in the main event of NJPW's 40th anniversary event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=517|script-title=ja:NJPW 40th anniversary \u65d7\u63da\u3052\u8a18\u5ff5\u65e5|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|accessdate=2012-03-04|language=Japanese}}</ref> On May 3 at [[Wrestling Dontaku 2012]], Okada defeated [[2012 New Japan Cup]] winner and reigning IWGP Intercontinental Champion Hirooki Goto to make his second successful title defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=543|script-title=ja:NJPW 40th anniversary \u30ec\u30b9\u30ea\u30f3\u30b0\u3069\u3093\u305f\u304f 2012|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|date=2012-05-03|accessdate=2012-05-03|language=Japanese}}</ref> On June 16 at [[Dominion 6.16]], Okada lost the IWGP Heavyweight Championship back to Hiroshi Tanahashi, ending his reign at 125 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=584|title=Dominion 6.16|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|date=2012-06-16|accessdate=2012-06-16|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nOn August 1, Okada entered his first [[G1 Climax#2012|G1 Climax tournament]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=597|script-title=ja:\u30ab\u30fc\u30c9\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30c8!! \u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30ac\u30fc\u30c9 Presents NJPW 40th anniversary Tour G1 Climax 22 \uff5eThe One And Only\uff5e|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|date=2012-08-01|accessdate=2012-08-05|language=Japanese}}</ref> In the tournament, Okada wrestled in the same block as Chaos leader Shinsuke Nakamura and, on August 5, was defeated by Nakamura, who effectively solidified his spot as the group's leader in the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=600|script-title=ja:\u30ab\u30fc\u30c9\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30c8!! \u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30ac\u30fc\u30c9 Presents NJPW 40th anniversary Tour G1 Climax 22 \uff5eThe One And Only\uff5e|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|date=2012-08-05|accessdate=2012-08-05|language=Japanese}}</ref> However, Okada bounced back from the loss, winning five of his eight [[Round-robin tournament|round-robin]] stage matches and finished at the top of his block, advancing to the finals of the tournament.<ref name=G1Climax2012Finals>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=605|script-title=ja:\u30ab\u30fc\u30c9\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30c8!! \u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30ac\u30fc\u30c9 Presents NJPW 40th anniversary Tour G1 Climax 22 \uff5eThe One And Only\uff5e|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|date=2012-08-12|accessdate=2012-08-12|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref name=G1Climax2012FinalsPWTorch>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/quicknews/article_64211.shtml|title=NJPW: Former TNA wrestler wins G1|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=2012-08-12|accessdate=2012-08-12|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> In the finals on August 12, Okada defeated [[Karl Anderson]] to win the 2012 G1 Climax.<ref name=G1Climax2012Finals/><ref name=G1Climax2012FinalsPWTorch/> Breaking [[Masahiro Chono]]'s record for the youngest G1 Climax winner in history, Okada announced that he wanted his shot at the IWGP Heavyweight Championship on January 4, 2013, at [[Wrestle Kingdom 7 in Tokyo Dome]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsnavi.yahoo.co.jp/fight/headlines/20120813-00000000-spnavi_nm-fight.html|script-title=ja:\u521d\u51fa\u5834\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u3001\u6700\u5e74\u5c11\u3067G1\u521d\u5236\u8987\u3082\u300c\u5f53\u7136\u306e\u3053\u3068\u300d=\u65b0\u65e5\u672c\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9|work=Sports Navi|date=2012-08-12|accessdate=2012-08-12|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|language=Japanese}}{{dead link|date=May 2017|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> Okada signed a contract for the Tokyo Dome match on September 6, making him the official number one contender to the IWGP Heavyweight Championship at NJPW's biggest event of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=8105|script-title=ja:\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u304c1.4\u6771\u4eac\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0\u306eIWGP\u738b\u5ea7\u6311\u6226\u201c\u6a29\u5229\u8a3c\u201d\u3092\u30b2\u30c3\u30c8!! \u3000\u3060\u304c\u83c5\u6797\u793e\u9577\u306f\u201c\u3042\u308b\u6761\u4ef6\u201d\u3092\u63d0\u793a!!|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|date=2012-09-06|accessdate=2012-09-06|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/quicknews/article_64921.shtml|title=NJPW Video - Former TNA wrestler's Tokyo Dome main event contract signing|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=2012-09-06|accessdate=2012-09-06|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> However, before January 4, Okada would have to defend his contract as if it were a championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/quicknews/article_64953.shtml|title=NJPW: Update on former TNA wrestler's Tokyo Dome main event quest|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=2012-09-07|accessdate=2012-09-07|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On October 8 at [[King of Pro-Wrestling (2012)|King of Pro-Wrestling]], Okada made his first successful defense of the contract against Karl Anderson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=619|title=NJPW 40th anniversary King of Pro-Wrestling|accessdate=2012-10-08|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014185115/http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=619|archivedate=2012-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1349710834|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121101154112/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1349710834|title=10/8 NJPW iPPV Results: Tokyo, Japan|last=Namako|first=Jason|archivedate=2012-11-01|date=2012-10-08|accessdate=2012-10-08|work=Wrestleview}}</ref> On November 11 at [[Power Struggle (2012)|Power Struggle]], Okada made another successful defense against Hirooki Goto. Later in the event, after Hiroshi Tanahashi had successfully defended the IWGP Heavyweight Championship against Yujiro Takahashi, the Tokyo Dome title match between him and Okada was made official.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=625|title=NJPW 40th anniversary Power Struggle|accessdate=2012-11-11|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1352765476|title=11/11 NJPW iPPV Results: Osaka, Japan|last=Namako|first=Jason|date=2012-11-12|accessdate=2012-11-13|work=Wrestleview|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117202001/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1352765476|archivedate=2012-11-17}}</ref> From November 20 to December 1, Okada took part in the round-robin portion of the [[2012 World Tag League]], alongside stablemate Yoshi-Hashi under the team name \"Chaos Ride the Lightning\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=8507|script-title=ja:11\u670820\u65e5(\u706b)\u958b\u5e55!!\u3000\u300eWorld Tag League 2012\u300f\u306e\u5bfe\u6226\u30ab\u30fc\u30c9\u6c7a\u5b9a!!\u3000TDC\u5927\u4f1a\u3001\u611b\u77e5\u5927\u4f1a\u306b\u306f\u685c\u5ead\uff06\u67f4\u7530\u304c\u7279\u5225\u53c2\u6226\uff01|date=2012-11-16|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|accessdate=2012-12-01|language=Japanese}}</ref> The team finished with a record of three wins and three losses, with a loss to Sword & Guns (Hirooki Goto and Karl Anderson) on the final day, costing them a spot in the semifinals of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=648|title=NJPW 40th anniversary Tour World Tag League 2012|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|accessdate=2012-12-01|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=654|title=NJPW 40\uff54\uff48 anniversary Tour World Tag League 2012|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|accessdate=2012-12-01|language=Japanese}}</ref> On December 10, ''[[Tokyo Sports]]'' named Okada the 2012 [[Tokyo Sports Puroresu Awards#MVP Award|MVP]] in all of ''[[puroresu]]''.<ref name=TokyoSports2012MVP>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/61838/|script-title=ja:\u300c\uff12\uff10\uff11\uff12\u5e74\u5ea6\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u5927\u8cde\u300d\u53d7\u8cde\u8005|date=2012-12-11|accessdate=2012-12-10|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref name=TokyoSports2012MVPNJPW>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=8661|script-title=ja:\u3010\u6700\u5e74\u5c11\u30bf\u30a4!!\u3011\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u304c\u300e\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u5927\u8cde\u300fMVP\u3092\u300c\u3042\u305f\u308a\u307e\u3048\u300d\u306e\u521d\u53d7\u8cde!! \u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\u30d0\u30a6\