2016) {{small|vs. Hiroshi Tanahashi on January 4}}<ref>{{cite magazine | last = Meltzer | first = Dave | authorlink = Dave Meltzer | date = March 6, 2017 | title = March 6, 2017 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: 2016 Awards issue, talent departing TNA, more | magazine = [[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]] | location = [[Campbell, California]] | issn = 1083-9593 | page=14}}</ref>\n**Pro Wrestling Match of the Year (2017) {{small|vs. Kenny Omega on January 4}}<ref name=\"WON17\"/>\n**Pro Wrestling Match of the Year (2018) {{small|vs. Kenny Omega on June 9}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.postwrestling.com/2019/03/17/bonus-show-wrestling-observer-newsletter-awards/|title=BONUS SHOW: Wrestling Observer Newsletter Awards|date=March 17, 2019|accessdate=March 23, 2019|work=Post Wrestling}}</ref>\n**[[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Wrestler of the Year|Wrestler of the Year]] (2017)<ref name=\"WON17\">{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/wrestling-observer-radio/wor-2017-wrestling-observer-newsletter-awards-discussion-and-more-253601|title=WOR: 2017 WRESTLING OBSERVER NEWSLETTER AWARDS DISCUSSION AND MORE!|last=Alvarez|first=Bryan|authorlink=Bryan Alvarez|date=March 15, 2018|accessdate=March 15, 2018|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref>\n**[[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Japan MVP|Japan MVP]] (2019)\n**Most Oustanding Wrestler of the Decade (2010s)<ref>https://www.f4wonline.com/daily-updates/daily-update-coronavirus-notes-noah-wrestlemania-307636</ref>\n**Best Matches of the Decade (2010s)<ref>https://www.f4wonline.com/daily-updates/daily-update-coronavirus-notes-noah-wrestlemania-307636</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{NJPW profile|id=1450|name=Kazuchika Okada|newlink=yes}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n* {{Instagram|rainmakerxokada}}\n* {{Youtube|rainmakerXokada|rainmakerXokada}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|ach}}\n{{succession box | title=[[G1 Climax]] winner|before=[[Shinsuke Nakamura]]<br>[[Tetsuya Naito]] | after=[[Tetsuya Naito]]<br>[[Hiroshi Tanahashi]]| years=2012<br>2014}}\n{{succession box | title=[[New Japan Cup]] winner|before=[[Hirooki Goto]]<br>[[Zack Sabre Jr.]] | after=[[Shinsuke Nakamura]]<br>Incumbent| years=2013<br>2019}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list1=\n{{Chaos (professional wrestling)}}\n{{IWGP Heavyweight Championship}}\n{{New Japan Cup}}\n{{New Japan Pro Wrestling personnel}}\n{{G1 Climax}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Okada, Kazuchika}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chaos (professional wrestling) members]]\n[[Category:IWGP Heavyweight champions]]\n[[Category:Japanese expatriates in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Japanese male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:People from Anj\u014d]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Aichi Prefecture]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eChampionships and accomplishments:Typo/generalfixes, replaced: Oustanding \u2192 Outstanding", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kazuchika_Okada"}
{"title_page": "Mithaecus", "text_new": "'''Mithaecus''' ([[Ancient Greek language|Ancient Greek]]: '''\u039c\u03af\u03b8\u03b1\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2''') was a [[Cook (profession)|cook]] and cookbook author of the late 5th century BC. A Greek-speaking native of [[Sicily]] at a time when the island was rich and highly civilized, Mithaecus is credited with having brought knowledge of [[Sicilian cuisine|Sicilian gastronomy]] to Greece.<ref>Dalby (2003), p. 220; Hill and Wilkins (1996), pp. 144-148.</ref> Specifically, according to sources of varying reliability, he worked in [[Sparta]], from which he was expelled as a bad influence,<ref>Maximus of Tyre. [https://www.google.com/books/edition/_/OW5KAAAAYAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1 ''Dissertations'', 7].</ref> and in [[Athens]]. He earned an unfavourable mention in [[Plato]]'s dialogue ''[[Gorgias]]''.<ref>Plato. ''Gorgias'', 518c.</ref>\n\nMithaecus is the first known author of any cookbook, and his is the first known (if not extant) Greek cookbook. One very brief recipe survives from it, thanks to a quotation in the ''[[Deipnosophistae]]'' of [[Athenaeus]]. It is in the [[Doric Greek|Doric]] dialect of Greek (appropriate both to Greek Sicily and to Sparta) and describes, in one line, how to deal with the fish ''[[Cepola macrophthalma]]'',<ref>Dalby (1996), pp. 109-110.</ref> a ribbon-like fish here called ''tainia'' (known in [[Italian language|Italian]] as ''cepola'' and in [[Greek language|modern Greek]] as ''kordella''):\n\n:''Tainia'': gut, discard the head, rinse, slice; add cheese and [olive] oil.<ref>Athenaeus. ''Deipnosophistae'', 325f; Bilabel (1920). English translation from Dalby (2003), p. 79.</ref>\n\nThe addition of cheese seems to have been a controversial matter; [[Archestratus]] is quoted as warning his readers that [[Syracusan]] cooks spoil good fish by adding cheese.<ref>Hill and Wilkins (1996), pp. 144-148.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|last=Bilabel|first=F.|title=Opsartytik\u00e1 und Verwandtes|url=https://archive.org/details/opsartytikaundv0bila|location=Heidelberg|year=1920}}\n* {{cite book | last=Dalby | first=Andrew | authorlink=Andrew Dalby | title=Siren Feasts | publisher=Routledge | location=Abingdon, Oxon, England | year=1996 | isbn=0-415-15657-2}}\n* {{cite book | last=Dalby | first=Andrew | title=Food in the ancient world from A to Z | publisher=Routledge | location=Abingdon, Oxon, England | year=2003 | isbn=0-415-23259-7}}\n* {{cite book|first=Shaun|last= Hill|first2=John|last2=Wilkins|contribution=Mithaikos and other Greek cooks|title=Cooks and other people: proceedings of the Oxford Symposium on Food and Cookery 1995|editor=Harlan Walker|location=Totnes|publisher=Prospect Books|year=1996}}\n\n[[Category:Sicilian Greeks]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek food writers]]\n[[Category:Writers of lost works]]\n[[Category:5th-century BC Greek people]]\n[[Category:Doric Greek writers]]\n[[Category:Writers of Magna Graecia]]\n", "text_old": "'''Mithaecus''' ([[Ancient Greek language|Ancient Greek]]: '''\u039c\u03af\u03b8\u03b1\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2''') was a [[Cook (profession)|cook]] and cookbook author of the late 5th century BC. A Greek-speaking native of [[Sicily]] at a time when the island was rich and highly civilized, Mithaecus is credited with having brought knowledge of [[Sicilian cuisine|Sicilian gastronomy]] to Greece.<ref>Dalby (2003), p. 220; Hill and Wilkins (1996), pp. 144-148.</ref> Specifically, according to sources of varying reliability, he worked in [[Sparta]], from which he was expelled as a bad influence,<ref>Maximus of Tyre. ''Dissertations'', 17.</ref> and in [[Athens]]. He earned an unfavourable mention in [[Plato]]'s dialogue ''[[Gorgias]]''.<ref>Plato. ''Gorgias'', 518c.</ref>\n\nMithaecus is the first known author of any cookbook, and his is the first known (if not extant) Greek cookbook. One very brief recipe survives from it, thanks to a quotation in the ''[[Deipnosophistae]]'' of [[Athenaeus]]. It is in the [[Doric Greek|Doric]] dialect of Greek (appropriate both to Greek Sicily and to Sparta) and describes, in one line, how to deal with the fish ''[[Cepola macrophthalma]]'',<ref>Dalby (1996), pp. 109-110.</ref> a ribbon-like fish here called ''tainia'' (known in [[Italian language|Italian]] as ''cepola'' and in [[Greek language|modern Greek]] as ''kordella''):\n\n:''Tainia'': gut, discard the head, rinse, slice; add cheese and [olive] oil.<ref>Athenaeus. ''Deipnosophistae'', 325f; Bilabel (1920). English translation from Dalby (2003), p. 79.</ref>\n\nThe addition of cheese seems to have been a controversial matter; [[Archestratus]] is quoted as warning his readers that [[Syracusan]] cooks spoil good fish by adding cheese.<ref>Hill and Wilkins (1996), pp. 144-148.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|last=Bilabel|first=F.|title=Opsartytik\u00e1 und Verwandtes|url=https://archive.org/details/opsartytikaundv0bila|location=Heidelberg|year=1920}}\n* {{cite book | last=Dalby | first=Andrew | authorlink=Andrew Dalby | title=Siren Feasts | publisher=Routledge | location=Abingdon, Oxon, England | year=1996 | isbn=0-415-15657-2}}\n* {{cite book | last=Dalby | first=Andrew | title=Food in the ancient world from A to Z | publisher=Routledge | location=Abingdon, Oxon, England | year=2003 | isbn=0-415-23259-7}}\n* {{cite book|first=Shaun|last= Hill|first2=John|last2=Wilkins|contribution=Mithaikos and other Greek cooks|title=Cooks and other people: proceedings of the Oxford Symposium on Food and Cookery 1995|editor=Harlan Walker|location=Totnes|publisher=Prospect Books|year=1996}}\n\n[[Category:Sicilian Greeks]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek food writers]]\n[[Category:Writers of lost works]]\n[[Category:5th-century BC Greek people]]\n[[Category:Doric Greek writers]]\n[[Category:Writers of Magna Graecia]]\n", "name_user": "Johntiptonyoung", "label": "safe", "comment": "It is the 7th Dissertation of Maximus of Tyre that discussed Mithaecus, not the 17th.", "