{"title_page": "90 West Street", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Short description|Residential skyscraper in Manhattan, New York}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                = 90 West Street\n| image               = 90 West Street April 2017.jpg\n| image_size          =\n| image_alt           =\n| image_caption       = Seen in April 2017\n| map_type            =\n| map_alt             =\n| map_caption         =\n| map_size            =\n| map_dot_label       =\n| map_dot_mark        =\n| former_names        = West Street Building, Coal & Iron Exchange, Railroad & Iron Exchange, Brady Building\n| alternate_names     =\n| etymology           =\n| status              =\n| cancelled           =\n| topped_out          =\n| building_type       = Residential (originally offices)\n| architectural_style = [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]]\n| classification      =\n| location            =\n| address             = 87-95 [[West Street (Manhattan)|West Street]]\n| location_city       = [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]], [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| location_country    = [[United States]]\n| coordinates         = {{coord|40|42|36|N|74|0|53|W|format=dms}}\n| altitude            =\n| current_tenants     =\n| namesake            =\n| groundbreaking_date =\n| start_date          = 1905\n| stop_date           =\n| est_completion      =\n| topped_out_date     =\n| completion_date     = 1907\n| opened_date         =\n| inauguration_date   =\n| relocated_date      =\n| renovation_date     = 2005\n| cost                =\n| ren_cost            =\n| client              =\n| owner               =\n| landlord            =\n| affiliation         =\n| height              = {{convert|324.02|ft|m}}\n| architectural       =\n| tip                 =\n| antenna_spire       =\n| roof                =\n| top_floor           =\n| observatory         =\n| diameter            =\n| circumference       =\n| weight              =\n| other_dimensions    =\n| structural_system   =\n| material            =\n| size                =\n| floor_count         = 23\n| floor_area          =\n| elevator_count      =\n| grounds_area        =\n| architect           = [[Cass Gilbert]]\n| architecture_firm   =\n| developer           =\n| engineer            =\n| structural_engineer = [[Gunvald Aus]]\n| services_engineer   =\n| civil_engineer      =\n| other_designers     =\n| quantity_surveyor   =\n| main_contractor     =\n| awards              =\n| designations        =\n| known_for           =\n| ren_architect       = H. Thomas O'Hara\n| ren_firm            =\n| ren_engineer        =\n| ren_str_engineer    =\n| ren_serv_engineer   =\n| ren_civ_engineer    =\n| ren_oth_designers   =\n| ren_qty_surveyor    =\n| ren_contractor      =\n| ren_awards          =\n| rooms               = <!-- or | unit_count          = -->\n| parking             =\n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| embedded            = {{Infobox NRHP\n  |embed = yes\n  | name = West Street Building\n  | image = 90 West Street Building.jpg\n  | caption = West Street Building before the [[September 11 attacks]]\n  | location= 90 West St., [[New York, New York]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|40|42|36|N|74|0|53|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Lower Manhattan#New York City\n  | area = {{convert|0.39|acre|ha}}\n  | added = January 25, 2007\n  | refnum = 06001303<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n  | governing_body = Private\n  | designated_other2_name = NYC Landmark\n | designated_other2_number = 1984\n| designated_other2_date = May 19, 1998\n| designated_other2_abbr = NYCL\n| designated_other2_link = New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission\n| designated_other2_color = #ffe978\n}}\n| references          = <ref name=\"emporis\"/>\n| footnotes           =\n}}\n'''90 West Street''' (previously known as the '''West Street Building''' and the '''Brady Building''') is a 23-story residential building in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Lower Manhattan]], [[New York City]]. It is located on a plot bounded by [[West Street (Manhattan)|West Street]] to the west, Cedar Street and the [[World Trade Center (2001\u2013present)|World Trade Center]] to the north, [[130 Cedar Street]] to the east, and [[Albany Street (Manhattan)|Albany Street]] to the south.\n\n90 West Street was designed by [[Cass Gilbert]], with [[Gunvald Aus]] and Burt Harrison as structural engineers, and John Peirce as general contractor. It was erected for the West Street Improvement Corporation, led by transportation magnate Howard Carroll.<ref>{{cite book |title=Guide to Civil Engineering Projects In and Around New York City |edition=2nd |publisher=Metropolitan Section, American Society of Civil Engineers |year=2009 |page=108}}</ref> The building's [[Gothic revival|Gothic]] styling and ornamentation served to emphasize its height. The design combined elements of the three-section \"classical column\" arrangement of 19th-century buildings with the \"romantic tower\" of Gilbert's later structures such as the [[Woolworth Building]]. Its waterfront site necessitated the installation of [[pilings]] deep into the ground. Other features included a [[architectural terracotta|terracotta]] facade with [[granite]] at the two-story base, as well as terracotta fireproofing inside the building.\n\n90 West Street was built in 1905\u20131907 as an office building called the West Street Building. \"The Garret Restaurant\", located on the structure's top floors, was marketed as being the highest restaurant in the world. The building underwent numerous ownership changes in the 20th century, and was known after its long-term owner, Brady Security and Realty Corporation, during the middle of the century. Following the [[collapse of the World Trade Center|collapse]] of the adjacent [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] in the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001, attacks]], the West Street Building was severely damaged. The building was subsequently refurbished extensively and it reopened as a residential building called 90 West in 2005.\n\n90 West Street's design was widely praised when it was originally completed. The building was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2007, and was designated a city landmark by the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] in 1998.\n\n== Site ==\n[[File:World Center Hotel & 90 West Street.jpg|left|thumb|[[130 Cedar Street]] (left) and 90 West Street (right) as seen from the [[National September 11 Memorial & Museum|National September 11 Memorial]] to the north]]\n90 West Street is located on a plot facing [[West Street (Manhattan)|West Street]] to the west, [[Cedar Street]] and the [[World Trade Center (2001\u2013present)|World Trade Center]] to the north, and [[Albany Street (Manhattan)|Albany Street]] to the south. The lot is roughly parallelogram-shaped.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> The building shares its block with [[130 Cedar Street]],<ref name=\"NYC.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://maps.nyc.gov/doitt/nycitymap/|title=NYCityMap|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Government of New York City|NYC.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Information Technology and Telecommunications]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref> a 19-story hotel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/176364/club-quarters-world-trade-center-new-york-city-ny-usa|title=Club Quarters World Trade Center|website=Emporis|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> 90 West Street carries the address numbers 87\u201395 West Street, inclusive,<ref name=\"NYC.gov\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 1\"/>{{efn|On West Street, this includes both even and odd numbered addresses.<ref name=\"NYC.gov\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\"/> Address numbers on the east side of West Street run consecutively because the west side of the street was formerly on the waterfront.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\"/> In the area's standard [[House numbering#North America|address numbering]] system, odd- and even-numbered addresses are on opposite sides of the street.<ref name=\"NYC.gov\" />}} as well as odd address numbers 21\u201325 Albany Street and even address numbers 136\u2013140 Cedar Street.<ref name=\"NYC.gov\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 1\"/>\n\nWhen built, the West Street Building overlooked the [[North River (Hudson River)|North River]] (now [[Hudson River]]) to the west.<ref name=\"Irish p. 380\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=380}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 12\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=12}}</ref> In the 1970s, [[Battery Park City]] was built on filled land along the shore of the river,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jacobson|first=Aileen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/15/realestate/battery-park-city-a-resort-like-community-built-on-landfill.html|title=Battery Park City: A Resort-Like Community Built on Landfill|date=August 15, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 7, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref> cutting off the West Street Building from the waterfront.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" />\n\n== Design ==\nThe West Street Building is {{convert|324|ft}} tall and contains 23 above-ground floors.<ref name=\"emporis\">{{cite web|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/114934/90-west-street-new-york-city-ny-usa|title=90 West Street|website=Emporis|access-date=May 3, 2017}}</ref> It was designed by [[Cass Gilbert]], who had designed numerous public structures and government buildings in the [[Beaux arts (architecture)|Beaux Arts]] style.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cassgilbertsociety.org/works/|title=Cass Gilbert \u2013 the Architect \u2013 Featured Works|website=Cass Gilbert Society|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> From the start, Gilbert intended the West Street Building as \"a machine that makes the land pay\".<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Irish p. 378\" /> In an article for the ''[[Engineering News-Record]]'', he wrote that in general, \"architectural beauty, judged even from an economic standpoint, has an income-bearing value\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gilbert|first=Cass|date=June 30, 1900|title=The Financial Importance of Rapid Building|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=chi.098727507&view=1up&seq=642|journal=Engineering Record|volume=41|pages=624|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe West Street Building was one of the first skyscrapers to consistently use [[Gothic Revival architecture|neo-Gothic]]-style decoration.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Irish pp. 395-396\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|pp=395\u2013396}}</ref> At the time, it was still relatively rare for a steel-skeleton skyscraper to contain [[architectural terracotta|terracotta]] cladding, as the West Street Building did.<ref name=\"Irish pp. 395-396\" /> The decoration was inspired by the [[Gothic architecture]] of Belgium, using religious models such as the [[St. Rumbold's Cathedral]] in [[Mechelen]], as well as secular models such as [[Brussels Town Hall]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"CFS 2001 p. 141\">{{harvnb|Christen|Flanders|Stern|2001|ps=.|p=141}}</ref> Furthermore, in his initial plans, Gilbert wanted to create a five-story tower that rose from the center of the structure, topping the height of the [[Flatiron Building]].<ref name=\"Irish p. 394\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=394}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=Jan 19, 1907|title=The West Street Building, New York, N.Y.|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=iau.31858033422696&view=1up&seq=7|journal=American Architect and Building News, International Edition|volume=91|at=Diagrams between pages 40 and 41|via=}}</ref> This five-story tower was canceled by Carroll, presumably to save money,<ref name=\"CFS 2001 p. 141\" /><ref name=\"Irish p. 394\" /> but the idea inspired the seven-story upper section of the building, topped by a [[mansard roof]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"CFS 2001 p. 141\" />\n\n=== Form ===\nThe West Street Building is 23 stories tall. The lower floors occupy the whole parallelogram-shaped lot, while the upper floors contain a \"C\"-shaped floor plan, with a small \"light court\" facing east toward the middle of the block.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5, NPS p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|p=5}}; {{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> To comply with the building laws of the 1900s, which required buildings over {{Convert|100|ft||abbr=}} to be able to withstand {{Convert|30|lb/ft2||abbr=}} of wind pressure, the West Street Building's steel superstructure was braced to protect against wind gusts. The [[Curtain wall (architecture)|curtain walls]] on the exterior were reinforced by hollow brick, while portal bracing was used for the steel frame.<ref name=\"Irish p. 387\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=387}}</ref>\n\n=== Facade ===\nAt the time of the West Street Building's construction, the facades of many 19th-century [[early skyscrapers]] consisted of three horizontal sections similar to the components of a [[column]]\u2014namely a base, shaft, and [[Capital (architecture)|capital]]\u2014in contrast to Gilbert's later skyscraper designs, which tended toward a \"romantic tower\" style.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> The West Street Building was one of four major Gilbert skyscrapers in the early 20th century, the others being the [[Second Brazer Building]] (1896), the [[Broadway\u2013Chambers Building]] (1900), and the [[Woolworth Building]] (1913). The West Street Building used a reduced version of the tripartite facade layout; compared to previous commissions, the \"base\" was scaled down, the \"shaft\" was emphasized by tall vertical [[Pier (architecture)|piers]], and the \"capital\" was emphasized by its Gothic-style mansard roof.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Irish pp. 395-396\" />\n\nThe West Street Building contains a base clad with granite. On the upper stories, the facade consists mostly of beige terracotta tiles manufactured by the [[Atlantic Terra Cotta Company]].<ref name=\"Irish p. 394\" /><ref name=\"Heilbrun 2000\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Inventing the skyline : the architecture of Cass Gilbert|date=2000|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2000|isbn=0-231-11872-4|editor-last=Heilbrun|editor-first=Margaret|location=New York|pages=3, 8, 115-117|oclc=43227473}}</ref><ref name=\"CG-Society\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cassgilbertsociety.org/works/nyc-west-street-bldg/|title=Cass Gilbert Society \u2013 Cass Gilbert \u2013 the Architect \u2013 Works \u2013 West Street Building, New York, NY|website=www.cassgilbertsociety.org|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> The terracotta facade is highlighted by red, green, blue, and gold tiles.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=4}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Tunick, Susan.|title=Terra-cotta skyline : New York's architectural ornament|date=1997|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|others=Mauss, Peter.|isbn=1-56898-105-8|edition=1st|location=New York|pages=59|oclc=36130720}}</ref> There are seven architectural [[Bay (architecture)|bays]] on the Cedar Street facade, nine bays along West Street, and six bays on Albany Street. The upper portion of the east facade is divided by the light court into two \"wings\": the northern wing contains four bays and the southern wing contains two bays.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5, NPS p. 4\" /> The eastern facade is mostly concealed from view, but the visible portions contain a similar design treatment as the three other facades.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7, NPS p. 7\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|p=7}}; {{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=7}}</ref>\n\n==== Base ====\nThe base is three stories tall and clad with Fox Island granite. There are segmental arches at ground level,<ref name=\"Irish p. 394\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 5, NPS p. 4\" /> and a [[cornice]] runs above the second story.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> At West Street, there are single-width arches within the outermost bays, and double-width arches in all the other bays. The center bay consists of a double-height arched entrance flanked by red marble columns, foliated [[Boss (architecture)|bosses]] with [[tracery]], and a sign saying {{Smallcaps|90 west st}}.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5, NPS p. 4\" /> The Albany and Cedar Street facades are largely set up similarly at the base, with single-width arches in the outer bays and double-width arches in the inner bays.<ref name=\"NYCL pp. 6-7, NPS p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|pp=6\u20137}}; {{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> The Cedar Street side has an offset arched entrance that is similar to the West Street entrance, with signage saying {{Smallcaps|140 cedar st}},<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=6}}</ref> while the Albany Street side has a driveway that leads down into a basement garage.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=7}}</ref> On all three sides, the remaining arches are double-height and contain wood, aluminum, or cast-iron storefronts.<ref name=\"NYCL pp. 6-7, NPS p. 5\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|p=6}}; {{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=5}}</ref>\n\nThe third story is designed as a \"transitional story\", with a cornice above the top. Between the window openings in each bay, there are granite panels, as well as foliated bosses at each corner of the window openings. The outermost bays contain one window each and are framed by more elaborate surrounds, while all the other bays contain two windows each. There are marble panels below the cornice, and single-story [[engaged column]]s at each corner of the building.<ref name=\"NYCL pp. 6-7, NPS p. 5\" /> Some of the granite [[lintel]]s are [[spall]]ed because they had been burned in the September 11 attacks.<ref name=\"NPS p. 5\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=5}}</ref>\n\n==== Shaft and crown ====\nThe \"shaft\" comprises the fourth through sixteenth stories. As with the base, the outer window bays consist of one window per floor, and the inner bays contain two windows per floor. Each bay is separated by piers that rise from the fourth to the fifteenth stories.<ref name=\"NYCL pp. 6-7, NPS p. 5\" /> There are iron balconies on the 14th floor. At the 15th floor, the piers end in foliated capitals, and the tops of the windows end in elaborate arches. Between each floor are terracotta [[spandrel]]s, which are recessed behind the piers. The 16th floor serves as another \"transitional story\" and its windows are surrounded by complex ornamentation.<ref name=\"NYCL pp. 6-7, NPS p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|p=6}}; {{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=6}}</ref> A cornice runs above the 16th floor.<ref name=\"NPS p. 6\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=6}}</ref>\n\n[[File:West Street Building (29149137660).jpg|left|thumb|Dormer windows Inserted in the copper-clad roof]]\nThe \"crown\" comprises the 17th through 20th floors. The 17th through 19th floors are designed as a triple-height [[Arcade (architecture)|arcade]]. The spandrels between the floors are decorated with multicolored floral motifs, while there is another ornate cornice above the 19th floor.<ref name=\"NYCL pp. 6-7, NPS p. 6\" /> On the 20th floor, there are groupings of two windows in the outer bays and three windows in the inner bays, with an elaborate [[colonette]]. There are figures of [[griffin]]s separating each window bay.<ref name=\"NYCL pp. 6-7, NPS p. 7\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|p=6}}; {{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=7}}</ref>\n\n==== Roof ====\nThe top three stories consist of a copper-clad mansard roof.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5, NPS p. 4\" /> There are [[dormer]] screens containing small balconies on the 21st floor, while the 22nd and 23rd floors contain dormer windows. These windows are covered by polygonal dormer roofs.<ref name=\"NYCL pp. 6-7, NPS p. 7\" /> Above the 23rd floor is an [[asphalt]] roof surface containing mechanical equipment as well as [[Bulkhead (barrier)|bulkheads]].<ref name=\"NPS p. 7\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=7}}</ref> The dormers, as well as decorative [[Tourelle (architecture)|tourelles]], added to the aesthetic of the building when it was originally viewed from the waterfront.<ref name=\"Irish p. 394\" />\n\n=== Foundation ===\nThe site was difficult to develop, as the [[bedrock]] layer was an average of {{Convert|50|ft||abbr=}} below the ground level of the site.<ref name=\"Irish p. 380\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=8}}</ref> The ground above the bedrock was composed of {{Convert|2|to|3|ft|abbr=}} of clay directly above, then a layer of sand, and finally {{Convert|20|ft||abbr=}} of mud and silt at ground level. Construction was further hindered by the difficulties in constructing [[Caisson (engineering)|caissons]] due to the frequent fires and air-pressure-related injuries associated with such structures.<ref name=\"Irish p. 380\" /> [[Gunvald Aus]], the structural engineer, dismissed the original plans for the foundation, which called for the usage of pneumatic caissons so that the foundation would be deep inside the rock. Instead, he decided to use [[pilings]] because he felt that it was sufficient for the layers of rock and [[hardpan]] to be immediately adjacent. Pilings had been previously used in two other Lower Manhattan buildings: the [[New York Produce Exchange]] and the [[Havemeyer Building]].<ref name=\"Irish p. 381\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=381}}</ref>\n\nThe foundation consisted of pilings that descended at least {{Convert|25|ft||abbr=}}, except at the boiler room where they descended {{Convert|18|ft||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Irish p. 381\" /> A layer of concrete, approximately {{Convert|11.5|in||abbr=}} thick, was then placed atop the pilings. The [[MetLife|Metropolitan Life Insurance Company]], the [[Underwriting|underwriter]] for general contractor John Peirce, initially did not insure the project because of concerns that the foundation would settle unevenly. Metropolitan Life finally agreed to insure the project after Aus performed a test, which found that a pile would settle {{Convert|3/8|in||abbr=}} when loaded with {{Convert|35|ST|LT t|abbr=}} of [[pig iron]].<ref name=\"Irish p. 382\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=382}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=May 12, 1906|title=Waterproofing the Substructure of the West Street Building, New York|url=|journal=Engineering Record|volume=53|pages=601|via=}}</ref>\n\nSeventy-four columns were drilled down to the rock. Due to the varying loads carried by each column, their sizes ranged from {{Convert|4|to|12|ft|abbr=}} square, composed of clusters of between 4 and 25 piles. Additionally, in the layer of concrete above the piles, there was a series of [[I-beam]]s that was encased in the concrete. Since the boundaries of the lot did not intersect at right angles, the columns carried varying weight distributions.<ref name=\"Irish p. 383\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=383}}</ref> The foundation work proceeded at an average depth of {{Convert|18|ft|m|abbr=}} below the Hudson River's [[Mean High Water|mean high water]], requiring extensive waterproofing. This contract was outsourced to the Sicilian Asphalt Paving Company, one of Carroll's companies.<ref>{{cite journal|year=1906|title=Waterproofing the Substructure of the West Street Building, New York|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z3lJAQAAMAAJ|journal=The Engineering Record, Building Record and the Sanitary Engineer|publisher=Henry C. Meyer|volume=53|page=601}}</ref><ref name=\"Irish p. 386\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=386}}</ref>\n\n=== Features ===\nThe lobby contains two corridors arranged in a \"T\" shape. One leads south from the Cedar Street entrance while the other extends east from the main entrance on West Street, terminating at the north-south corridor. Five elevators are located on the east wall of the lobby, opposite the West Street entrance, and are arranged in an arc.<ref name=\"NPS p. 7\" /> As built, there were nine \"plunger elevators\", five of which could operate at the same time.<ref name=\"Irish p. 389\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=389}}</ref> A [[mailroom]] is located on the southern side of the lobby section leading from Cedar Street, while a concierge desk is located on the southern side of the section from West Street. The floor is made of marble tile while the ceiling consists of [[groin vault]]s made of plaster; both were installed after a 2005 renovation. Within the lobby, there are now-closed arches leading to the ground-floor retail spaces.<ref name=\"NPS p. 8\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=8}}</ref> The retail areas themselves were configured with entrances to the street and to the lobby, but did not have interior partitions. While the retail spaces' original finishes were burned and removed after the September 11 attacks, they received new concrete floors and [[gypsum]] ceilings and wall panels during the 2005 renovation.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=9}}</ref>\n\nThe upper floors contained {{Convert|200,000|ft2||abbr=}} of leasable office space, with an average of {{Convert|10,000|ft2||abbr=}} per floor.<ref name=\"wsj19200426\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46253530/|title=American Sugar Benefits From Rise in Realty Values|date=April 26, 1920|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 6, 2020|page=3|issn=0099-9660|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> The floors could be arranged to allow a myriad of office layouts. All elevators served the upper stories.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> The National Fireproofing Company manufactured the interior terracotta fireproofing.<ref name=\"Heilbrun 2000\" /><ref name=\"CG-Society\" /> During the 2005 renovation, these were converted into residential apartments, and gypsum paneling was installed on the walls. Additionally, a fitness center was installed at the bottom of the light court on the second floor.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> \n\nThe West Street Building's small footprint and waterside location meant that there was little room for the building's mechanical equipment, the layout of which had been designed mostly by Burt Harrison.<ref name=\"Irish p. 389\" /> On one basement level, there were four {{Convert|250|hp||abbr=}} boilers, six {{Convert|550|kW||abbr=|adj=on|disp=flip}} power generators, elevator equipment, and rooms in which {{Convert|200|ST|LT t|abbr=}} of coal could be stored.<ref name=\"Irish p. 388\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=388}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=July 27, 1907|title=Power Plant of the West Street Building, New York City|url=https://archive.org/stream/engineeringrecor56newyuoft/engineeringrecor56newyuoft_djvu.txt|journal=Engineering Record|volume=56|pages=95\u201398|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> Radiators were placed underneath each window, with heat provided by a system of low-pressure exhaust pipes, since the site could be subject to heat losses on windy days. Originally, there was no artificial ventilation except in part of the basement.<ref name=\"Irish p. 389\" />\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Planning and construction ===\n[[File:West Street building LCCN2003676567.jpg|thumb|An early print of the West Street Building]]\nThe 1898 formation of the [[City of Greater New York]] resulted in a sharp increase in the number of buildings being erected in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Lower Manhattan]], and by the 1900s decade, the neighborhood had 40 new office buildings.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=3}}</ref><ref name=\"Irish (1985) p. 234\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Irish|1985|p=234}}</ref> These included the [[United States Express Building]] (2 Rector Street), the [[Singer Building]], and the [[Old New York Evening Post Building]], which were under construction in the middle of that decade.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> Among the interested developers was the West Street Improvement Company, a collection of businesspersons in Lower Manhattan. The company, headquartered in the Broadway\u2013Chambers Building, was led by Howard Carroll,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=2}}</ref><ref name=\"Irish p. 378\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=378}}</ref> and co-founded by John Peirce, Walter Roberts, and Judge S. P. McConnell.<ref name=\"Irish p. 391\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Irish|1989|p=391}}</ref>\n\nThe West Street Improvement Company sought to erect an office structure particularly for the shipping interests along the Hudson River, the shoreline of which was located at West Street during the early 1900s.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Zeisloft|first=E. Idell|title=The new metropolis; 1600-memorable events of three centuries-1900; from the island of Mana-hat-ta to Greater New York at the close of the nineteenth century, edited by E. Idell Zeisloft. Illustrated with one thousand engravings.|date=1899|publisher=D. Appleton|isbn=|location=New York|pages=586|language=English|oclc=82929613}}</ref><ref name=\"Irish p. 390\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Irish|1989|p=390}}</ref> They selected a site between Albany and Cedar Streets with a lot length of {{Convert|159|ft||abbr=}} facing West Street.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> The adjacent buildings on West Street contained warehouses and other facilities dedicated toward the railroad and steamship industries.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref name=\"Irish p. 391\" /> Furthermore, the future site of the West Street Building was directly across West Street from ferry piers and docks, which in turn led to major ferry and rail terminals on the other side of the Hudson River.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Irish p. 390\" />\n\nCarroll hired Gilbert to create a design in April 1905.<ref name=\"Irish p. 380\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /> Gunvald Aus and Burt Harrison were commissioned as the structural engineers while John Peirce was retained as the general contractor.<ref name=\"Irish p. 380\" /> The same year, the West Street Improvement Company and Gilbert submitted documents to the [[New York City Department of Buildings]], proposing a 23-to-28 story office building that would cost about $2 million to build.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> Architecture professor Sharon Irish identified \"fourteen preliminary sketches that include plans, elevations, and perspectives\" for the building, varying in their level of detail.<ref name=\"Irish p. 394\" /> The design had to attract the more than 100,000 ferry passengers that traveled between New Jersey and New York each day, many of whom visited the building's rooftop.<ref name=\"Irish p. 396\" /><ref name=\"CFS 2001 p. 140\">{{harvnb|Christen|Flanders|Stern|2001|ps=.|p=140}}</ref> The building's construction started in April 1906 and the structure was finished the next year.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" />\n\n=== 20th-century use ===\nAccording to a pamphlet for the West Street Building, \"the building commends itself particularly to railroads, engineers, dock builders, contractors, lawyers, shippers, and machinery and electrical trades\".<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref name=\"Irish p. 391\" /> The main tenant was the [[Delaware, Lackawanna and Western Railroad]], which operated both the nearby [[Cortlandt Street Ferry Depot]] as well as [[Hoboken Terminal]] across the Hudson River.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Irish (1985) p. 221\">{{harvnb|Irish|1985|ps=.|p=221}}</ref> This led to the building being nicknamed the \"Railroad and Iron Exchange Building\"<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Irish p. 392\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=392}}</ref><ref name=\"NPS p. 12\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=12}}</ref> and alternatively as the \"Coal and Iron Building\".<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" /><ref name=\"Landau p. 321\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Landau|1996|p=321}}</ref> The top floor was occupied by Garret's Restaurant, which advertised itself as the \"world's highest restaurant\"<ref name=\"nyt2004-03-05\">{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Glenn|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/03/05/nyregion/9-11-s-miracle-survivor-sheds-bandages-1907-landmark-will-be-restored-for.html|title=9/11's Miracle Survivor Sheds Bandages; A 1907 Landmark Will Be Restored for Residential Use|date=March 5, 2004|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=March 13, 2010|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref name=\"downtown express\">{{cite news|last=Amateau|first=Albert|url=http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=3874672&BRD=1841&PAG=461&dept_id=112709&rfi=6|title=L.M.D.C. Looks to Restore Cass Gilbert Building|date=April 17, 2002|newspaper=Downtown Express|accessdate=March 13, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061212013658/http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=3874672&BRD=1841&PAG=461&dept_id=112709&rfi=6|archivedate=December 12, 2006}}</ref> and was later characterized as the forerunner to World Trade Center's [[Windows on the World]] restaurant.<ref name=\"Irish p. 392\" /> Other tenants included West Street Improvement Company's own members, including Carroll's firm Sicilian Asphalt Paving Company as well as the John Peirce Company.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref name=\"Irish p. 391\" />\n\nThe [[American Sugar Refining Company]] (ASR) bought the West Street Building from the West Street Improvement Company in 1913 for $4.5 million.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=17}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1913/12/12/archives/the-real-estate-field-american-sugar-refining-company-buys-west.html|title=The Real Estate Field; American Sugar Refining Company Buys West Street Building in $4,500,000 Deal|date=December 12, 1913|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref> In partial exchange, ASR sold some property in the [[Long Island City]] neighborhood of [[Queens]],<ref name=\"wsj19200426\" /> as well as some property in [[Brooklyn]].<ref name=\":1\" /> The ASR held the West Street Building as an investment, occupying a small portion of the structure. By 1920 the West Street Building was estimated to be worth $3.5 million, though ASR initially refused to sell.<ref name=\"wsj19200426\" />\n\nIn 1923, the Brady Security and Realty Corporation bought the building from ASR,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1923/04/13/issue.html|title=$3,500,000 Sale on West Street|date=April 13, 1923|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2020|url-status=live|page=29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|via=TimesMachine|url-access=limited}}</ref> and the West Street Building subsequently became the '''Brady Building'''.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /> The elevators, first-floor interior, office space and mechanical systems were refurbished during the early 1930s. During the renovation, the original first-floor interior's arches and groin vaults were removed, though the facade received few modifications.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/1125443522/A27C4E8239BA41A5PQ|title=Brady Estate Renovating West Street Building|work=New York Herald-Tribune|date=December 13, 1932|access-date=March 4, 2020|via=ProQuest|url-access=subscription|page=30}}</ref> Further modifications in the mid-20th century resulted in the renovation of the entrances and storefronts, as well as the addition of exterior nighttime lighting and air-conditioning grilles.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> Brady sold the building in 1952 to Louis Schleifer for $2.7 million.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1952/05/25/issue.html|title=Schleifer Obtains Downtown Offices|date=May 25, 1952|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2020|url-status=live|page=R1|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|via=TimesMachine|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The \"Brady Building\" name persisted over several years, despite being sold multiple times through the end of the 20th century. The lobby was renovated in the 1960s and 1980s, which led to the removal of many of the original finishes.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /> The building's exterior was designated an architectural [[landmark]] by the city's [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission|Landmarks Preservation Commission]] in 1998,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 1\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=1}}</ref> though the interior was not similarly designated.<ref name=\"nyt2004-03-05\" />\n\n=== Damage, renovation, and residential use ===\n[[File:The Ground Zero Area - panoramio (11).jpg|thumb|Seen from across West Street]]The building was severely damaged in the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001, attacks]] when the South Tower of the World Trade Center collapsed {{convert|300|ft}} away. Scaffolding, which had been erected on the facade for renovation work, failed to prevent debris from falling onto the building. Debris tore a number of large gashes in its northern facade,<ref name=\"downtown express\" /> including one gap between the third and 11th floors.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Glanz|first=James|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/12/04/science/wounded-buildings-offer-survival-lessons.html|title=Wounded Buildings Offer Survival Lessons|date=December 4, 2001|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref> Several remains of 9/11 victims landed on the northern scaffolding and were not retrieved until 2003.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/10/us/two-years-later-remains-found-near-ground-zero.html|title=Two Years Later; Remains Found Near Ground Zero|date=September 10, 2003|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2020|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref> Two office workers were killed when they were trapped in an elevator.<ref name=\"nyt2004-03-05\" />\n\nThe [[firestorm]] continued for several days; the interior light court functioned as a chimney, causing further damage to the interior.<ref name=\"NPS p. 18\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=18}}</ref> The West Street Building's heavy building materials and extensive use of [[architectural terracotta|terracotta]] may have helped serve as fireproofing and protected it from further damage and collapse, as opposed to the more modern skyscraper at [[7 World Trade Center]], which suffered similar damage and collapsed on the afternoon of September 11.<ref name=\":2\" /> Nevertheless, falling steel from the World Trade Center resulted in the destruction of the ground-floor [[Morton's The Steakhouse]] franchise.<ref name=\"nyt2004-03-05\" /> Following the attacks, a large American flag was flown outside the West Street Building,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2014/05/21/911-memorial-museum-opens-to-public-as-special-flag-is-unfurled/|title=9/11 Memorial Museum opens to public, as special flag is unfurled|last=Hiatt|first=Anna|date=May 21, 2014|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> which became a \"symbol of hope\" for 9/11 rescuers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/a-torn-9-11-flag-is-repaired-one-loving-stitch-at-a-time|title=A Torn 9/11 Flag is Repaired, One Loving Stitch at a Time|last=Foster|first=Kathleen|date=March 25, 2015|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBrack Capital Real Estate bought the West Street Building in January 2003, intending to restore the structure.<ref name=\"NPS p. 18\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/17/nyregion/metro-briefing-new-york-manhattan-building-near-ground-zero-is-sold.html|title=Metro Briefing; New York: Manhattan: Building Near Ground Zero Is Sold|date=January 17, 2003|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2020|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref> Because of the scale of the destruction, as well as the fact that the interior was not officially protected, the inner floors were completely renovated, and plastic sheeting was placed across the north facade to cover the damage. The [[December 2003 nor'easter]] tore open a portion of the sheeting, which was then removed.<ref name=\"nyt2004-03-05\" /> The developers were subsequently given $106.5 million in federal [[Bond (finance)|bonds]] to renovate the building. Restoration of the lobby revealed some of Gilbert's original terracotta work that had been covered over during an earlier modernization project. During this restoration, the copper roof was replaced for $4 million; the granite base was restored for $5 million; replacement gargoyles were added; and over 7,000 replica terracotta tiles were added.<ref name=\"NPS p. 18\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Collins|first=Glenn|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/02/28/nyregion/faces-at-least-a-city-can-love.html|title=Faces at Least a City Can Love|date=February 28, 2005|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 5, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref> A parking garage was also built in the building's basement.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|last=Lambert|first=Bruce|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/27/nyregion/27flood.html|title=Manhattan Building Evacuated After Flood Forces Power Cut|date=2007-11-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-08|last2=Hughes|first2=C. J.|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The interior was converted into apartments and reopened in mid-2005 as 90 West Street, a 410-unit residential building.<ref name=\"NPS p. 18\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2005-06-27-0506270163-story.html|title=Reborn 9/11 building gives WTC district breath of life|last=Swanson|first=Stevenson|date=June 27, 2005|website=Chicago Tribune|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> The next year, it received a National Preservation Honor Award from the National Trust for Historic Preservation.<ref>{{cite press release|title=National Trust Presents National Preservation Honor Award to 90 West Street in Lower Manhattan|publisher=National Trust for Historic Preservation|date=November 2, 2006|url=http://www.preservationnation.org/take-action/awards/national-preservation-awards/90-west-street-building-2006.html|access-date=November 6, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309142402/http://www.preservationnation.org/take-action/awards/national-preservation-awards/90-west-street-building-2006.html|archive-date=March 9, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n\n90 West Street was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on January 25, 2007.<ref name=\"nris\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/subjects/nationalregister/upload/weekly-list-2007-national-register-of-historic-places.pdf|title=National Register of Historic Places 2007 Weekly Lists|date=2007|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]], [[National Park Service]] |access-date=March 8, 2020|page=37}}</ref> The designation included the exterior and part of the interior.<ref name=\"NPS p. 1\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=1}}</ref> The building was slightly damaged in November 2007, when a large sewer pipe from the [[World Trade Center site]] burst open and flooded the basement,<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wabc/story?section=news/local&id=5784823|title=Downtown Parking Garage Under Water; Residents Evacuated|date=November 26, 2007|work=WABC|accessdate=2010-03-13}}</ref> causing a two-week evacuation of the building.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pinto|first=Nick|title=90 West Street Residents Wary of Waivers|date=December 12, 2007|newspaper=Tribeca Tribune}}</ref> The operators of the [[National September 11 Memorial & Museum]] proposed in 2011 to use 90 West Street as a screening site,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rubinstein|first=Dana|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703864204576311332813557162|title=At 9/11 Site, Built-In Hurdles|date=May 9, 2011|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 5, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> which was controversial among the building's residents.<ref>{{cite web | last=Shapiro | first=Julie | title=Plan to Screen 9/11 Tourists in Luxury Building Irks Residents | website=DNAinfo New York | date=April 20, 2011 | url=https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20110420/downtown/plan-screen-911-tourists-luxury-condo-irks-residents | access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archpaper.com/2011/06/access-denied/|title=Access Denied|first=Molly|last=Heintz|date=June 13, 2011|website=Archpaper|language=en-US|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> Despite this, 90 West Street ended up being utilized as a visitors' center for people traveling to the memorial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribecatrib.com/content/memorial-chief-expects-freely-accessed-plaza-next-year|title=Memorial Chief Expects 'Freely Accessed' Plaza by Next Year|last=Reynolds|first=Aline|date=July 12, 2013|website=Tribeca Trib Online|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> Tenants of 90 West Street filed a lawsuit in the 2010s, stating that the building's then-owners had wrongfully eliminated [[rent regulation]] for the building's residential units. In 2019, the [[New York Supreme Court]] ruled in the tenants' favor, since the owners had received benefits under the 421-g tax incentive program, and were thus bound to provide stabilized leases for the tenants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://therealdeal.com/2019/06/25/tenants-score-another-win-lower-manhattan-apartments-shouldve-been-rent-regulated-court-rules/|title=421G Case Goes in Favor of Tenants in Lower Manhattan|date=June 25, 2019|website=The Real Deal New York|language=en-US|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thecity.nyc/2019/08/tenants-of-6-000-downtown-apartments-may-be-owed-back-rent.html|title=Tenants of 6,000 Downtown Apartments May Be Owed Back Rent|last=Holliday Smith|first=Rachel|date=August 12, 2019|website=The City|language=en|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thevillager.com/2019/07/lower-manhattan-tenants-win-appeals-court-ruling-on-rent-regulation/|title=FiDi tenants win fight to keep rent regulation|date=July 20, 2019|website=The Villager|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n[[File:The Ground Zero Area - panoramio (5).jpg|thumb|Top of the building]]\nUpon its opening, the West Street Building was lauded by other architects and artists.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> The architectural critic [[Montgomery Schuyler]], in a 1919 ''[[Scribner's Magazine]]'' article, noted that the West Street Building was uncommon in that it was praised by both the public and by architectural critics.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=5}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Schuyler|first=Montgomery|date=September 1909|title=The Evolution of the Skyscraper|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.319510019200199&view=1up&seq=299|journal=Scribner's Magazine|volume=46|pages=257\u2013271|via=HathiTrust}}</ref> [[John Merven Carr\u00e8re]], a partner in the architectural firm [[Carr\u00e8re and Hastings]], said to Gilbert that \"I think it is the most successful building of its class.\"<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Irish (1985) p. 248\">{{harvnb|Irish|1985|ps=.|p=248}}</ref> [[Edwin Blashfield]], a painter, wrote a letter to Gilbert to tell him \"what a splendid impression your West Street Building makes on one, as one comes up the harbor on the way back from the other side of the Atlantic.\"<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Irish p. 396\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=396}}</ref>\n\nArchitectural critics approved of the building's design as well. An anonymous writer for the ''[[Architectural Record]]'', possibly Schuyler,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> said that he appreciated the upper stories, as well as the design of the vertical piers and the Gothic ornamentation.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=August 1907|title=The West Street Building|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=gri.ark:/13960/t3b05zj49&view=1up&seq=120|journal=Architectural Record|volume=22|pages=108|via=HathiTrust}}</ref> Another writer for the ''Architectural Record'' stated in 1909 that the structure was \"an aesthetic and technical triumph\" and \"the work of a master mind.\"<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bragdon|first=Claude|date=July 1909|title=Architecture in the United States: III. The Skyscraper|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044039466933&view=1up&seq=274|journal=Architectural Record|volume=26|pages=96|via=HathiTrust}}</ref> In 1912, a writer for the ''[[Architectural Review]]'' said that the use of ornament and the expression of the building's design \"account for the excellence of effect of the West Street Building.\"<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Swales|first=Francis S.|date=January 1912|title=The Work of Cass Gilbert|url=|journal=Architectural Review|volume=31|pages=16|via=}}</ref>\n\nPraise for the West Street Building continued even through later years, such as a 1934 article which called the structure among the city's \"most satisfying buildings.\"<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kirkham|first=Guy|date=1934|title=Cass Gilbert, Master of Style|url=|journal=Pencil Points|volume=15|pages=548|via=}}</ref> [[Ada Louise Huxtable]], speaking about a proposed Lower Manhattan development district in 1970, said that the area \"contains a few gems of substance such as Cass Gilbert's Beaux-Arts Brady Building on West Street.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Huxtable|first=Ada Louise|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/12/06/archives/an-appraisal-concept-points-to-city-of-future.html|title=An Appraisal|date=December 6, 1970|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=subscription}}</ref> [[Herbert Muschamp]] wrote in 1998 that, following the 1970s completion of the much taller World Trade Center, \"Contemporary critics evidently found it painful to praise Gilbert's West Street Building\" but that the \"wedding cake top\" of the mansard roof \"looks edible\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Muschamp|first=Herbert|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/10/09/arts/critic-s-notebook-cass-gilbert-and-the-city-eclectic.html|title=Critic's Notebook; Cass Gilbert And the City Eclectic|date=October 9, 1998|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref> The [[National Park Service]], in its 2007 historic-designation report, stated that in addition to 90 West Street's importance as one of the first skyscrapers to consistently use of Gothic detailing, the structure \"acquired additional historical importance as a witness to and survivor of the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001.\"<ref name=\"NPS p. 11\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=11}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Architecture|New York City|NRHP}}\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Manhattan below 14th Street]]\n* [[List of New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan below 14th Street]]\n* [[Verizon Building]], another nearby building damaged in the 9/11 attacks\n\n{{-}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{Commons category|90 West Street}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Christen|first1=B.S.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x3X_D6L5JEwC&pg=PA294|title=Cass Gilbert, Life and Work: Architect of the Public Domain|last2=Flanders|first2=S.|last3=Stern|first3=R.A.M.|publisher=W.W. Norton|year=2001|isbn=978-0-393-73065-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/NARAprodstorage/lz/electronic-records/rg-079/NPS_NY/06001303.pdf|title=Historic Structures Report: West Street Building|date=December 12, 2006|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]], [[National Park Service]]|ref={{harvid|National Park Service|2006}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Irish|first=Sharon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0kKYwwEACAAJ|title=Cass Gilbert's Career in New York, 1899\u20131905|publisher=Northwestern University|year=1985|ref={{harvid|Irish|1985}}}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Irish|first=Sharon|date=April 1989|title=A 'Machine That Makes the Land Pay': The West Street Building in New York|journal=Technology and Culture|volume=30|issue=2|pages=376\u2013397|doi=10.2307/3105109|jstor=3105109|ref={{harvid|Irish|1989}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Landau|first=Sarah|title=Rise of the New York skyscraper, 1865\u20131913|publisher=Yale University Press|year=1996|isbn=978-0-300-07739-1|location=New Haven|oclc=32819286|ref={{harvid|Landau|1996}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1984.pdf|title=West Street Building|date=May 19, 1998|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York|state=collapsed}}\n{{New York City Historic Sites}}\n{{Financial District, Manhattan}}\n{{World Trade Center}}\n\n[[Category:Skyscraper office buildings in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Cass Gilbert buildings]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1907]]\n[[Category:Financial District, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:National Historic Landmarks in New York City]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:West Side Highway]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Short description|Residential skyscraper in Manhattan, New York}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                = 90 West Street\n| image               = 90 West Street April 2017.jpg\n| image_size          =\n| image_alt           =\n| image_caption       = Seen in April 2017\n| map_type            =\n| map_alt             =\n| map_caption         =\n| map_size            =\n| map_dot_label       =\n| map_dot_mark        =\n| former_names        = West Street Building, Coal & Iron Exchange, Railroad & Iron Exchange, Brady Building\n| alternate_names     =\n| etymology           =\n| status              =\n| cancelled           =\n| topped_out          =\n| building_type       = Residential (originally offices)\n| architectural_style = [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]]\n| classification      =\n| location            =\n| address             = 87-95 [[West Street (Manhattan)|West Street]]\n| location_city       = [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]], [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| location_country    = [[United States]]\n| coordinates         = {{coord|40|42|36|N|74|0|53|W|format=dms}}\n| altitude            =\n| current_tenants     =\n| namesake            =\n| groundbreaking_date =\n| start_date          = 1905\n| stop_date           =\n| est_completion      =\n| topped_out_date     =\n| completion_date     = 1907\n| opened_date         =\n| inauguration_date   =\n| relocated_date      =\n| renovation_date     = 2005\n| cost                =\n| ren_cost            =\n| client              =\n| owner               =\n| landlord            =\n| affiliation         =\n| height              = {{convert|324.02|ft|m}}\n| architectural       =\n| tip                 =\n| antenna_spire       =\n| roof                =\n| top_floor           =\n| observatory         =\n| diameter            =\n| circumference       =\n| weight              =\n| other_dimensions    =\n| structural_system   =\n| material            =\n| size                =\n| floor_count         = 23\n| floor_area          =\n| elevator_count      =\n| grounds_area        =\n| architect           = [[Cass Gilbert]]\n| architecture_firm   =\n| developer           =\n| engineer            =\n| structural_engineer = [[Gunvald Aus]]\n| services_engineer   =\n| civil_engineer      =\n| other_designers     =\n| quantity_surveyor   =\n| main_contractor     =\n| awards              =\n| designations        =\n| known_for           =\n| ren_architect       = H. Thomas O'Hara\n| ren_firm            =\n| ren_engineer        =\n| ren_str_engineer    =\n| ren_serv_engineer   =\n| ren_civ_engineer    =\n| ren_oth_designers   =\n| ren_qty_surveyor    =\n| ren_contractor      =\n| ren_awards          =\n| rooms               = <!-- or | unit_count          = -->\n| parking             =\n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| embedded            = {{Infobox NRHP\n  |embed = yes\n  | name = West Street Building\n  | image = 90 West Street Building.jpg\n  | caption = West Street Building before the [[September 11 attacks]]\n  | location= 90 West St., [[New York, New York]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|40|42|36|N|74|0|53|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Lower Manhattan#New York City\n  | area = {{convert|0.39|acre|ha}}\n  | added = January 25, 2007\n  | refnum = 06001303<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n  | governing_body = Private\n  | designated_other2_name = NYC Landmark\n | designated_other2_number = 1984\n| designated_other2_date = May 19, 1998\n| designated_other2_abbr = NYCL\n| designated_other2_link = New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission\n| designated_other2_color = #ffe978\n}}\n| references          = <ref name=\"emporis\"/>\n| footnotes           =\n}}\n'''90 West Street''' (previously known as the '''West Street Building''' and the '''Brady Building''') is a 23-story residential building in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Lower Manhattan]], [[New York City]]. It is located on a plot bounded by [[West Street (Manhattan)|West Street]] to the west, Cedar Street and the [[World Trade Center (2001\u2013present)|World Trade Center]] to the north, [[130 Cedar Street]] to the east, and [[Albany Street (Manhattan)|Albany Street]] to the south.\n\n90 West Street was designed by [[Cass Gilbert]], with [[Gunvald Aus]] and Burt Harrison as structural engineers, and John Peirce as general contractor. It was erected for the West Street Improvement Corporation, led by transportation magnate Howard Carroll.<ref>{{cite book |title=Guide to Civil Engineering Projects In and Around New York City |edition=2nd |publisher=Metropolitan Section, American Society of Civil Engineers |year=2009 |page=108}}</ref> The building's [[Gothic revival|Gothic]] styling and ornamentation served to emphasize its height. The design combined elements of the three-section \"classical column\" arrangement of 19th-century buildings with the \"romantic tower\" of Gilbert's later structures such as the [[Woolworth Building]]. Its waterfront site necessitated the installation of [[pilings]] deep into the ground. Other features included a [[architectural terracotta|terracotta]] facade with [[granite]] at the two-story base, as well as terracotta fireproofing inside the building.\n\n90 West Street was built in 1905\u20131907 as an office building called the West Street Building. \"The Garret Restaurant\", located on the structure's top floors, was marketed as being the highest restaurant in the world. The building underwent numerous ownership changes in the 20th century, and was known after its long-term owner, Brady Security and Realty Corporation, during the middle of the century. Following the [[collapse of the World Trade Center|collapse]] of the adjacent [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] in the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001, attacks]], the West Street Building was severely damaged. The building was subsequently refurbished extensively and it reopened as a residential building called 90 West in 2005.\n\n90 West Street's design was widely praised when it was originally completed. The building was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2007, and was designated a city landmark by the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] in 1998.\n\n== Site ==\n[[File:World Center Hotel & 90 West Street.jpg|left|thumb|[[130 Cedar Street]] (left) and 90 West Street (right) as seen from the [[National September 11 Memorial & Museum|National September 11 Memorial]] to the north]]\n90 West Street is located on a plot facing [[West Street (Manhattan)|West Street]] to the west, [[Cedar Street]] and the [[World Trade Center (2001\u2013present)|World Trade Center]] to the north, and [[Albany Street (Manhattan)|Albany Street]] to the south. The lot is roughly parallelogram-shaped.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> The building shares its block with [[130 Cedar Street]],<ref name=\"NYC.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://maps.nyc.gov/doitt/nycitymap/|title=NYCityMap|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Government of New York City|NYC.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Information Technology and Telecommunications]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref> a 19-story hotel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/176364/club-quarters-world-trade-center-new-york-city-ny-usa|title=Club Quarters World Trade Center|website=Emporis|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> 90 West Street carries the address numbers 87\u201395 West Street, inclusive,<ref name=\"NYC.gov\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 1\"/>{{efn|On West Street, this includes both even and odd numbered addresses.<ref name=\"NYC.gov\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\"/> Address numbers on the east side of West Street run consecutively because the west side of the street was formerly on the waterfront.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\"/> In the area's standard [[House numbering#North America|address numbering]] system, odd- and even-numbered addresses are on opposite sides of the street.<ref name=\"NYC.gov\" />}} as well as odd address numbers 21\u201325 Albany Street and even address numbers 136\u2013140 Cedar Street.<ref name=\"NYC.gov\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 1\"/>\n\nWhen built, the West Street Building overlooked the [[North River (Hudson River)|North River]] (now [[Hudson River]]) to the west.<ref name=\"Irish p. 380\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=380}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 12\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=12}}</ref> In the 1970s, [[Battery Park City]] was built on filled land along the shore of the river,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jacobson|first=Aileen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/15/realestate/battery-park-city-a-resort-like-community-built-on-landfill.html|title=Battery Park City: A Resort-Like Community Built on Landfill|date=August 15, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 7, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref> cutting off the West Street Building from the waterfront.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" />\n\n== Design ==\nThe West Street Building is {{convert|324|ft}} tall and contains 23 above-ground floors.<ref name=\"emporis\">{{cite web|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/114934/90-west-street-new-york-city-ny-usa|title=90 West Street|website=Emporis|access-date=May 3, 2017}}</ref> It was designed by [[Cass Gilbert]], who had designed numerous public structures and government buildings in the [[Beaux arts (architecture)|Beaux Arts]] style.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cassgilbertsociety.org/works/|title=Cass Gilbert \u2013 the Architect \u2013 Featured Works|website=Cass Gilbert Society|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> From the start, Gilbert intended the West Street Building as \"a machine that makes the land pay\".<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Irish p. 378\" /> In an article for the ''[[Engineering News-Record]]'', he wrote that in general, \"architectural beauty, judged even from an economic standpoint, has an income-bearing value\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gilbert|first=Cass|date=June 30, 1900|title=The Financial Importance of Rapid Building|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=chi.098727507&view=1up&seq=642|journal=Engineering Record|volume=41|pages=624|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe West Street Building was one of the first skyscrapers to consistently use [[Gothic Revival architecture|neo-Gothic]]-style decoration.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Irish pp. 395-396\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|pp=395\u2013396}}</ref> At the time, it was still relatively rare for a steel-skeleton skyscraper to contain [[architectural terracotta|terracotta]] cladding, as the West Street Building did.<ref name=\"Irish pp. 395-396\" /> The decoration was inspired by the [[Gothic architecture]] of Belgium, using religious models such as the [[St. Rumbold's Cathedral]] in [[Mechelen]], as well as secular models such as [[Brussels Town Hall]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"CFS 2001 p. 141\">{{harvnb|Christen|Flanders|Stern|2001|ps=.|p=141}}</ref> Furthermore, in his initial plans, Gilbert wanted to create a five-story tower that rose from the center of the structure, topping the height of the [[Flatiron Building]].<ref name=\"Irish p. 394\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=394}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=Jan 19, 1907|title=The West Street Building, New York, N.Y.|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=iau.31858033422696&view=1up&seq=7|journal=American Architect and Building News, International Edition|volume=91|at=Diagrams between pages 40 and 41|via=}}</ref> This five-story tower was canceled by Carroll, presumably to save money,<ref name=\"CFS 2001 p. 141\" /><ref name=\"Irish p. 394\" /> but the idea inspired the seven-story upper section of the building, topped by a [[mansard roof]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"CFS 2001 p. 141\" />\n\n=== Form ===\nThe West Street Building is 23 stories tall. The lower floors occupy the whole parallelogram-shaped lot, while the upper floors contain a \"C\"-shaped floor plan, with a small \"light court\" facing east toward the middle of the block.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5, NPS p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|p=5}}; {{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> To comply with the building laws of the 1900s, which required buildings over {{Convert|100|ft||abbr=}} to be able to withstand {{Convert|30|lb/ft2||abbr=}} of wind pressure, the West Street Building's steel superstructure was braced to protect against wind gusts. The [[Curtain wall (architecture)|curtain walls]] on the exterior were reinforced by hollow brick, while portal bracing was used for the steel frame.<ref name=\"Irish p. 387\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=387}}</ref>\n\n=== Facade ===\nAt the time of the West Street Building's construction, the facades of many 19th-century [[early skyscrapers]] consisted of three horizontal sections similar to the components of a [[column]]\u2014namely a base, shaft, and [[Capital (architecture)|capital]]\u2014in contrast to Gilbert's later skyscraper designs, which tended toward a \"romantic tower\" style.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> The West Street Building was one of four major Gilbert skyscrapers in the early 20th century, the others being the [[Second Brazer Building]] (1896), the [[Broadway\u2013Chambers Building]] (1900), and the [[Woolworth Building]] (1913). The West Street Building used a reduced version of the tripartite facade layout; compared to previous commissions, the \"base\" was scaled down, the \"shaft\" was emphasized by tall vertical [[Pier (architecture)|piers]], and the \"capital\" was emphasized by its Gothic-style mansard roof.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Irish pp. 395-396\" />\n\nThe West Street Building contains a base clad with granite. On the upper stories, the facade consists mostly of beige terracotta tiles manufactured by the [[Atlantic Terra Cotta Company]].<ref name=\"Irish p. 394\" /><ref name=\"Heilbrun 2000\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Inventing the skyline : the architecture of Cass Gilbert|date=2000|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2000|isbn=0-231-11872-4|editor-last=Heilbrun|editor-first=Margaret|location=New York|pages=3, 8, 115-117|oclc=43227473}}</ref><ref name=\"CG-Society\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cassgilbertsociety.org/works/nyc-west-street-bldg/|title=Cass Gilbert Society \u2013 Cass Gilbert \u2013 the Architect \u2013 Works \u2013 West Street Building, New York, NY|website=www.cassgilbertsociety.org|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> The terracotta facade is highlighted by red, green, blue, and gold tiles.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=4}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Tunick, Susan.|title=Terra-cotta skyline : New York's architectural ornament|date=1997|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|others=Mauss, Peter.|isbn=1-56898-105-8|edition=1st|location=New York|pages=59|oclc=36130720}}</ref> There are seven architectural [[Bay (architecture)|bays]] on the Cedar Street facade, nine bays along West Street, and six bays on Albany Street. The upper portion of the east facade is divided by the light court into two \"wings\": the northern wing contains four bays and the southern wing contains two bays.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5, NPS p. 4\" /> The eastern facade is mostly concealed from view, but the visible portions contain a similar design treatment as the three other facades.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7, NPS p. 7\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|p=7}}; {{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=7}}</ref>\n\n==== Base ====\nThe base is three stories tall and clad with Fox Island granite. There are segmental arches at ground level,<ref name=\"Irish p. 394\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 5, NPS p. 4\" /> and a [[cornice]] runs above the second story.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> At West Street, there are single-width arches within the outermost bays, and double-width arches in all the other bays. The center bay consists of a double-height arched entrance flanked by red marble columns, foliated [[Boss (architecture)|bosses]] with [[tracery]], and a sign saying {{Smallcaps|90 west st}}.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5, NPS p. 4\" /> The Albany and Cedar Street facades are largely set up similarly at the base, with single-width arches in the outer bays and double-width arches in the inner bays.<ref name=\"NYCL pp. 6-7, NPS p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|pp=6\u20137}}; {{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> The Cedar Street side has an offset arched entrance that is similar to the West Street entrance, with signage saying {{Smallcaps|140 cedar st}},<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=6}}</ref> while the Albany Street side has a driveway that leads down into a basement garage.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=7}}</ref> On all three sides, the remaining arches are double-height and contain wood, aluminum, or cast-iron storefronts.<ref name=\"NYCL pp. 6-7, NPS p. 5\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|p=6}}; {{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=5}}</ref>\n\nThe third story is designed as a \"transitional story\", with a cornice above the top. Between the window openings in each bay, there are granite panels, as well as foliated bosses at each corner of the window openings. The outermost bays contain one window each and are framed by more elaborate surrounds, while all the other bays contain two windows each. There are marble panels below the cornice, and single-story [[engaged column]]s at each corner of the building.<ref name=\"NYCL pp. 6-7, NPS p. 5\" /> Some of the granite [[lintel]]s are [[spall]]ed because they had been burned in the September 11 attacks.<ref name=\"NPS p. 5\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=5}}</ref>\n\n==== Shaft and crown ====\nThe \"shaft\" comprises the fourth through sixteenth stories. As with the base, the outer window bays consist of one window per floor, and the inner bays contain two windows per floor. Each bay is separated by piers that rise from the fourth to the fifteenth stories.<ref name=\"NYCL pp. 6-7, NPS p. 5\" /> There are iron balconies on the 14th floor. At the 15th floor, the piers end in foliated capitals, and the tops of the windows end in elaborate arches. Between each floor are terracotta [[spandrel]]s, which are recessed behind the piers. The 16th floor serves as another \"transitional story\" and its windows are surrounded by complex ornamentation.<ref name=\"NYCL pp. 6-7, NPS p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|p=6}}; {{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=6}}</ref> A cornice runs above the 16th floor.<ref name=\"NPS p. 6\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=6}}</ref>\n\n[[File:West Street Building (29149137660).jpg|left|thumb|Dormer windows Inserted in the copper-clad roof]]\nThe \"crown\" comprises the 17th through 20th floors. The 17th through 19th floors are designed as a triple-height [[Arcade (architecture)|arcade]]. The spandrels between the floors are decorated with multicolored floral motifs, while there is another ornate cornice above the 19th floor.<ref name=\"NYCL pp. 6-7, NPS p. 6\" /> On the 20th floor, there are groupings of two windows in the outer bays and three windows in the inner bays, with an elaborate [[colonette]]. There are figures of [[griffin]]s separating each window bay.<ref name=\"NYCL pp. 6-7, NPS p. 7\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|p=6}}; {{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=7}}</ref>\n\n==== Roof ====\nThe top three stories consist of a copper-clad mansard roof.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5, NPS p. 4\" /> There are [[dormer]] screens containing small balconies on the 21st floor, while the 22nd and 23rd floors contain dormer windows. These windows are covered by polygonal dormer roofs.<ref name=\"NYCL pp. 6-7, NPS p. 7\" /> Above the 23rd floor is an [[asphalt]] roof surface containing mechanical equipment as well as [[Bulkhead (barrier)|bulkheads]].<ref name=\"NPS p. 7\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=7}}</ref> The dormers, as well as decorative [[Tourelle (architecture)|tourelles]], added to the aesthetic of the building when it was originally viewed from the waterfront.<ref name=\"Irish p. 394\" />\n\n=== Foundation ===\nThe site was difficult to develop, as the [[bedrock]] layer was an average of {{Convert|50|ft||abbr=}} below the ground level of the site.<ref name=\"Irish p. 380\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=8}}</ref> The ground above the bedrock was composed of {{Convert|2|to|3|ft|abbr=}} of clay directly above, then a layer of sand, and finally {{Convert|20|ft||abbr=}} of mud and silt at ground level. Construction was further hindered by the difficulties in constructing [[Caisson (engineering)|caissons]] due to the frequent fires and air-pressure-related injuries associated with such structures.<ref name=\"Irish p. 380\" /> [[Gunvald Aus]], the structural engineer, dismissed the original plans for the foundation, which called for the usage of pneumatic caissons so that the foundation would be deep inside the rock. Instead, he decided to use [[pilings]] because he felt that it was sufficient for the layers of rock and [[hardpan]] to be immediately adjacent. Pilings had been previously used in two other Lower Manhattan buildings: the [[New York Produce Exchange]] and the [[Havemeyer Building]].<ref name=\"Irish p. 381\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=381}}</ref>\n\nThe foundation consisted of pilings that descended at least {{Convert|25|ft||abbr=}}, except at the boiler room where they descended {{Convert|18|ft||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Irish p. 381\" /> A layer of concrete, approximately {{Convert|11.5|in||abbr=}} thick, was then placed atop the pilings. The [[MetLife|Metropolitan Life Insurance Company]], the [[Underwriting|underwriter]] for general contractor John Peirce, initially did not insure the project because of concerns that the foundation would settle unevenly. Metropolitan Life finally agreed to insure the project after Aus performed a test, which found that a pile would settle {{Convert|3/8|in||abbr=}} when loaded with {{Convert|35|ST|LT t|abbr=}} of [[pig iron]].<ref name=\"Irish p. 382\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=382}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=May 12, 1906|title=Waterproofing the Substructure of the West Street Building, New York|url=|journal=Engineering Record|volume=53|pages=601|via=}}</ref>\n\nSeventy-four columns were drilled down to the rock. Due to the varying loads carried by each column, their sizes ranged from {{Convert|4|to|12|ft|abbr=}} square, composed of clusters of between 4 and 25 piles. Additionally, in the layer of concrete above the piles, there was a series of [[I-beam]]s that was encased in the concrete. Since the boundaries of the lot did not intersect at right angles, the columns carried varying weight distributions.<ref name=\"Irish p. 383\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=383}}</ref> The foundation work proceeded at an average depth of {{Convert|18|ft|m|abbr=}} below the Hudson River's [[Mean High Water|mean high water]], requiring extensive waterproofing. This contract was outsourced to the Sicilian Asphalt Paving Company, one of Carroll's companies.<ref>{{cite journal|year=1906|title=Waterproofing the Substructure of the West Street Building, New York|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z3lJAQAAMAAJ|journal=The Engineering Record, Building Record and the Sanitary Engineer|publisher=Henry C. Meyer|volume=53|page=601}}</ref><ref name=\"Irish p. 386\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=386}}</ref>\n\n=== Features ===\nThe lobby contains two corridors arranged in a \"T\" shape. One leads south from the Cedar Street entrance while the other extends east from the main entrance on West Street, terminating at the north-south corridor. Five elevators are located on the east wall of the lobby, opposite the West Street entrance, and are arranged in an arc.<ref name=\"NPS p. 7\" /> As built, there were nine \"plunger elevators\", five of which could operate at the same time.<ref name=\"Irish p. 389\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=389}}</ref> A [[mailroom]] is located on the southern side of the lobby section leading from Cedar Street, while a concierge desk is located on the southern side of the section from West Street. The floor is made of marble tile while the ceiling consists of [[groin vault]]s made of plaster; both were installed after a 2005 renovation. Within the lobby, there are now-closed arches leading to the ground-floor retail spaces.<ref name=\"NPS p. 8\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=8}}</ref> The retail areas themselves were configured with entrances to the street and to the lobby, but did not have interior partitions. While the retail spaces' original finishes were burned and removed after the September 11 attacks, they received new concrete floors and [[gypsum]] ceilings and wall panels during the 2005 renovation.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=9}}</ref>\n\nThe upper floors contained {{Convert|200,000|ft2||abbr=}} of leasable office space, with an average of {{Convert|10,000|ft2||abbr=}} per floor.<ref name=\"wsj19200426\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46253530/|title=American Sugar Benefits From Rise in Realty Values|date=April 26, 1920|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 6, 2020|page=3|issn=0099-9660|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> The floors could be arranged to allow a myriad of office layouts. All elevators served the upper stories.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> The National Fireproofing Company manufactured the interior terracotta fireproofing.<ref name=\"Heilbrun 2000\" /><ref name=\"CG-Society\" /> During the 2005 renovation, these were converted into residential apartments, and gypsum paneling was installed on the walls. Additionally, a fitness center was installed at the bottom of the light court on the second floor.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> \n\nThe West Street Building's small footprint and waterside location meant that there was little room for the building's mechanical equipment, the layout of which had been designed mostly by Burt Harrison.<ref name=\"Irish p. 389\" /> On one basement level, there were four {{Convert|250|hp||abbr=}} boilers, six {{Convert|550|kW||abbr=|adj=on|disp=flip}} power generators, elevator equipment, and rooms in which {{Convert|200|ST|LT t|abbr=}} of coal could be stored.<ref name=\"Irish p. 388\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=388}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=July 27, 1907|title=Power Plant of the West Street Building, New York City|url=https://archive.org/stream/engineeringrecor56newyuoft/engineeringrecor56newyuoft_djvu.txt|journal=Engineering Record|volume=56|pages=95\u201398|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> Radiators were placed underneath each window, with heat provided by a system of low-pressure exhaust pipes, since the site could be subject to heat losses on windy days. Originally, there was no artificial ventilation except in part of the basement.<ref name=\"Irish p. 389\" />\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Planning and construction ===\n[[File:West Street building LCCN2003676567.jpg|thumb|An early print of the West Street Building]]\nThe 1898 formation of the [[City of Greater New York]] resulted in a sharp increase in the number of buildings being erected in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Lower Manhattan]], and by the 1900s decade, the neighborhood had 40 new office buildings.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=3}}</ref><ref name=\"Irish (1985) p. 234\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Irish|1985|p=234}}</ref> These included the [[United States Express Building]] (2 Rector Street), the [[Singer Building]], and the [[Old New York Evening Post Building]], which were under construction in the middle of that decade.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> Among the interested developers was the West Street Improvement Company, a collection of businesspersons in Lower Manhattan. The company, headquartered in the Broadway\u2013Chambers Building, was led by Howard Carroll,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=2}}</ref><ref name=\"Irish p. 378\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=378}}</ref> and co-founded by John Peirce, Walter Roberts, and Judge S. P. McConnell.<ref name=\"Irish p. 391\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Irish|1989|p=391}}</ref>\n\nThe West Street Improvement Company sought to erect an office structure particularly for the shipping interests along the Hudson River, the shoreline of which was located at West Street during the early 1900s.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Zeisloft|first=E. Idell|title=The new metropolis; 1600-memorable events of three centuries-1900; from the island of Mana-hat-ta to Greater New York at the close of the nineteenth century, edited by E. Idell Zeisloft. Illustrated with one thousand engravings.|date=1899|publisher=D. Appleton|isbn=|location=New York|pages=586|language=English|oclc=82929613}}</ref><ref name=\"Irish p. 390\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Irish|1989|p=390}}</ref> They selected a site between Albany and Cedar Streets with a lot length of {{Convert|159|ft||abbr=}} facing West Street.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> The adjacent buildings on West Street contained warehouses and other facilities dedicated toward the railroad and steamship industries.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref name=\"Irish p. 391\" /> Furthermore, the future site of the West Street Building was directly across West Street from ferry piers and docks, which in turn led to major ferry and rail terminals on the other side of the Hudson River.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Irish p. 390\" />\n\nCarroll hired Gilbert to create a design in April 1905.<ref name=\"Irish p. 380\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /> Gunvald Aus and Burt Harrison were commissioned as the structural engineers while John Peirce was retained as the general contractor.<ref name=\"Irish p. 380\" /> The same year, the West Street Improvement Company and Gilbert submitted documents to the [[New York City Department of Buildings]], proposing a 23-to-28 story office building that would cost about $2 million to build.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> Architecture professor Sharon Irish identified \"fourteen preliminary sketches that include plans, elevations, and perspectives\" for the building, varying in their level of detail.<ref name=\"Irish p. 394\" /> The design had to attract the more than 100,000 ferry passengers that traveled between New Jersey and New York each day, many of whom visited the building's rooftop.<ref name=\"Irish p. 396\" /><ref name=\"CFS 2001 p. 140\">{{harvnb|Christen|Flanders|Stern|2001|ps=.|p=140}}</ref> The building's construction started in April 1906 and the structure was finished the next year.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" />\n\n=== 20th-century use ===\nAccording to a pamphlet for the West Street Building, \"the building commends itself particularly to railroads, engineers, dock builders, contractors, lawyers, shippers, and machinery and electrical trades\".<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref name=\"Irish p. 391\" /> The main tenant was the [[Delaware, Lackawanna and Western Railroad]], which operated both the nearby [[Cortlandt Street Ferry Depot]] as well as [[Hoboken Terminal]] across the Hudson River.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Irish (1985) p. 221\">{{harvnb|Irish|1985|ps=.|p=221}}</ref> This led to the building being nicknamed the \"Railroad and Iron Exchange Building\"<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Irish p. 392\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=392}}</ref><ref name=\"NPS p. 12\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=12}}</ref> and alternatively as the \"Coal and Iron Building\".<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" /><ref name=\"Landau p. 321\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Landau|1996|p=321}}</ref> The top floor was occupied by Garret's Restaurant, which advertised itself as the \"world's highest restaurant\"<ref name=\"nyt2004-03-05\">{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Glenn|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/03/05/nyregion/9-11-s-miracle-survivor-sheds-bandages-1907-landmark-will-be-restored-for.html|title=9/11's Miracle Survivor Sheds Bandages; A 1907 Landmark Will Be Restored for Residential Use|date=March 5, 2004|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=March 13, 2010|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref name=\"downtown express\">{{cite news|last=Amateau|first=Albert|url=http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=3874672&BRD=1841&PAG=461&dept_id=112709&rfi=6|title=L.M.D.C. Looks to Restore Cass Gilbert Building|date=April 17, 2002|newspaper=Downtown Express|accessdate=March 13, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061212013658/http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=3874672&BRD=1841&PAG=461&dept_id=112709&rfi=6|archivedate=December 12, 2006}}</ref> and was later characterized as the forerunner to World Trade Center's [[Windows on the World]] restaurant.<ref name=\"Irish p. 392\" /> Other tenants included West Street Improvement Company's own members, including Carroll's firm Sicilian Asphalt Paving Company as well as the John Peirce Company.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref name=\"Irish p. 391\" />\n\nThe [[American Sugar Refining Company]] (ASR) bought the West Street Building from the West Street Improvement Company in 1913 for $4.5 million.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=17}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1913/12/12/archives/the-real-estate-field-american-sugar-refining-company-buys-west.html|title=The Real Estate Field; American Sugar Refining Company Buys West Street Building in $4,500,000 Deal|date=December 12, 1913|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref> In partial exchange, ASR sold some property in the [[Long Island City]] neighborhood of [[Queens]],<ref name=\"wsj19200426\" /> as well as some property in [[Brooklyn]].<ref name=\":1\" /> The ASR held the West Street Building as an investment, occupying a small portion of the structure. By 1920 the West Street Building was estimated to be worth $3.5 million, though ASR initially refused to sell.<ref name=\"wsj19200426\" />\n\nIn 1923, the Brady Security and Realty Corporation bought the building from ASR,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1923/04/13/issue.html|title=$3,500,000 Sale on West Street|date=April 13, 1923|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2020|url-status=live|page=29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|via=TimesMachine|url-access=limited}}</ref> and the West Street Building subsequently became the '''Brady Building'''.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /> The elevators, first-floor interior, office space and mechanical systems were refurbished during the early 1930s. During the renovation, the original first-floor interior's arches and groin vaults were removed, though the facade received few modifications.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/1125443522/A27C4E8239BA41A5PQ|title=Brady Estate Renovating West Street Building|work=New York Herald-Tribune|date=December 13, 1932|access-date=March 4, 2020|via=ProQuest|url-access=subscription|page=30}}</ref> Further modifications in the mid-20th century resulted in the renovation of the entrances and storefronts, as well as the addition of exterior nighttime lighting and air-conditioning grilles.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> Brady sold the building in 1952 to Louis Schleifer for $2.7 million.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1952/05/25/issue.html|title=Schleifer Obtains Downtown Offices|date=May 25, 1952|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2020|url-status=live|page=R1|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|via=TimesMachine|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The \"Brady Building\" name persisted over several years, despite being sold multiple times through the end of the 20th century. The lobby was renovated in the 1960s and 1980s, which led to the removal of many of the original finishes.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /> The building's exterior was designated an architectural [[landmark]] by the city's [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission|Landmarks Preservation Commission]] in 1998,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 1\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=1}}</ref> though the interior was not similarly designated.<ref name=\"nyt2004-03-05\" />\n\n=== Damage, renovation, and residential use ===\n[[File:The Ground Zero Area - panoramio (11).jpg|thumb|Seen from across West Street]]The building was severely damaged in the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001, attacks]] when the South Tower of the World Trade Center collapsed {{convert|300|ft}} away. Scaffolding, which had been erected on the facade for renovation work, failed to prevent debris from falling onto the building. Debris tore a number of large gashes in its northern facade,<ref name=\"downtown express\" /> including one gap between the third and 11th floors.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Glanz|first=James|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/12/04/science/wounded-buildings-offer-survival-lessons.html|title=Wounded Buildings Offer Survival Lessons|date=December 4, 2001|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref> Several remains of 9/11 victims landed on the northern scaffolding and were not retrieved until 2003.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/10/us/two-years-later-remains-found-near-ground-zero.html|title=Two Years Later; Remains Found Near Ground Zero|date=September 10, 2003|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2020|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref> Two office workers were killed when they were trapped in an elevator.<ref name=\"nyt2004-03-05\" />\n\nThe [[firestorm]] continued for several days; the interior light court functioned as a chimney, causing further damage to the interior.<ref name=\"NPS p. 18\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=18}}</ref> The West Street Building's heavy building materials and extensive use of [[archiectural terracotta|terracotta]] may have helped serve as fireproofing and protected it from further damage and collapse, as opposed to the more modern skyscraper at [[7 World Trade Center]], which suffered similar damage and collapsed on the afternoon of September 11.<ref name=\":2\" /> Nevertheless, falling steel from the World Trade Center resulted in the destruction of the ground-floor [[Morton's The Steakhouse]] franchise.<ref name=\"nyt2004-03-05\" /> Following the attacks, a large American flag was flown outside the West Street Building,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2014/05/21/911-memorial-museum-opens-to-public-as-special-flag-is-unfurled/|title=9/11 Memorial Museum opens to public, as special flag is unfurled|last=Hiatt|first=Anna|date=May 21, 2014|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> which became a \"symbol of hope\" for 9/11 rescuers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/a-torn-9-11-flag-is-repaired-one-loving-stitch-at-a-time|title=A Torn 9/11 Flag is Repaired, One Loving Stitch at a Time|last=Foster|first=Kathleen|date=March 25, 2015|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBrack Capital Real Estate bought the West Street Building in January 2003, intending to restore the structure.<ref name=\"NPS p. 18\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/17/nyregion/metro-briefing-new-york-manhattan-building-near-ground-zero-is-sold.html|title=Metro Briefing; New York: Manhattan: Building Near Ground Zero Is Sold|date=January 17, 2003|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2020|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref> Because of the scale of the destruction, as well as the fact that the interior was not officially protected, the inner floors were completely renovated, and plastic sheeting was placed across the north facade to cover the damage. The [[December 2003 nor'easter]] tore open a portion of the sheeting, which was then removed.<ref name=\"nyt2004-03-05\" /> The developers were subsequently given $106.5 million in federal [[Bond (finance)|bonds]] to renovate the building. Restoration of the lobby revealed some of Gilbert's original terracotta work that had been covered over during an earlier modernization project. During this restoration, the copper roof was replaced for $4 million; the granite base was restored for $5 million; replacement gargoyles were added; and over 7,000 replica terracotta tiles were added.<ref name=\"NPS p. 18\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Collins|first=Glenn|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/02/28/nyregion/faces-at-least-a-city-can-love.html|title=Faces at Least a City Can Love|date=February 28, 2005|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 5, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref> A parking garage was also built in the building's basement.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|last=Lambert|first=Bruce|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/27/nyregion/27flood.html|title=Manhattan Building Evacuated After Flood Forces Power Cut|date=2007-11-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-08|last2=Hughes|first2=C. J.|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The interior was converted into apartments and reopened in mid-2005 as 90 West Street, a 410-unit residential building.<ref name=\"NPS p. 18\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2005-06-27-0506270163-story.html|title=Reborn 9/11 building gives WTC district breath of life|last=Swanson|first=Stevenson|date=June 27, 2005|website=Chicago Tribune|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> The next year, it received a National Preservation Honor Award from the National Trust for Historic Preservation.<ref>{{cite press release|title=National Trust Presents National Preservation Honor Award to 90 West Street in Lower Manhattan|publisher=National Trust for Historic Preservation|date=November 2, 2006|url=http://www.preservationnation.org/take-action/awards/national-preservation-awards/90-west-street-building-2006.html|access-date=November 6, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309142402/http://www.preservationnation.org/take-action/awards/national-preservation-awards/90-west-street-building-2006.html|archive-date=March 9, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n\n90 West Street was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on January 25, 2007.<ref name=\"nris\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/subjects/nationalregister/upload/weekly-list-2007-national-register-of-historic-places.pdf|title=National Register of Historic Places 2007 Weekly Lists|date=2007|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]], [[National Park Service]] |access-date=March 8, 2020|page=37}}</ref> The designation included the exterior and part of the interior.<ref name=\"NPS p. 1\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=1}}</ref> The building was slightly damaged in November 2007, when a large sewer pipe from the [[World Trade Center site]] burst open and flooded the basement,<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wabc/story?section=news/local&id=5784823|title=Downtown Parking Garage Under Water; Residents Evacuated|date=November 26, 2007|work=WABC|accessdate=2010-03-13}}</ref> causing a two-week evacuation of the building.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pinto|first=Nick|title=90 West Street Residents Wary of Waivers|date=December 12, 2007|newspaper=Tribeca Tribune}}</ref> The operators of the [[National September 11 Memorial & Museum]] proposed in 2011 to use 90 West Street as a screening site,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rubinstein|first=Dana|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703864204576311332813557162|title=At 9/11 Site, Built-In Hurdles|date=May 9, 2011|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 5, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> which was controversial among the building's residents.<ref>{{cite web | last=Shapiro | first=Julie | title=Plan to Screen 9/11 Tourists in Luxury Building Irks Residents | website=DNAinfo New York | date=April 20, 2011 | url=https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20110420/downtown/plan-screen-911-tourists-luxury-condo-irks-residents | access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archpaper.com/2011/06/access-denied/|title=Access Denied|first=Molly|last=Heintz|date=June 13, 2011|website=Archpaper|language=en-US|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> Despite this, 90 West Street ended up being utilized as a visitors' center for people traveling to the memorial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribecatrib.com/content/memorial-chief-expects-freely-accessed-plaza-next-year|title=Memorial Chief Expects 'Freely Accessed' Plaza by Next Year|last=Reynolds|first=Aline|date=July 12, 2013|website=Tribeca Trib Online|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> Tenants of 90 West Street filed a lawsuit in the 2010s, stating that the building's then-owners had wrongfully eliminated [[rent regulation]] for the building's residential units. In 2019, the [[New York Supreme Court]] ruled in the tenants' favor, since the owners had received benefits under the 421-g tax incentive program, and were thus bound to provide stabilized leases for the tenants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://therealdeal.com/2019/06/25/tenants-score-another-win-lower-manhattan-apartments-shouldve-been-rent-regulated-court-rules/|title=421G Case Goes in Favor of Tenants in Lower Manhattan|date=June 25, 2019|website=The Real Deal New York|language=en-US|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thecity.nyc/2019/08/tenants-of-6-000-downtown-apartments-may-be-owed-back-rent.html|title=Tenants of 6,000 Downtown Apartments May Be Owed Back Rent|last=Holliday Smith|first=Rachel|date=August 12, 2019|website=The City|language=en|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thevillager.com/2019/07/lower-manhattan-tenants-win-appeals-court-ruling-on-rent-regulation/|title=FiDi tenants win fight to keep rent regulation|date=July 20, 2019|website=The Villager|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n[[File:The Ground Zero Area - panoramio (5).jpg|thumb|Top of the building]]\nUpon its opening, the West Street Building was lauded by other architects and artists.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> The architectural critic [[Montgomery Schuyler]], in a 1919 ''[[Scribner's Magazine]]'' article, noted that the West Street Building was uncommon in that it was praised by both the public and by architectural critics.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=5}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Schuyler|first=Montgomery|date=September 1909|title=The Evolution of the Skyscraper|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.319510019200199&view=1up&seq=299|journal=Scribner's Magazine|volume=46|pages=257\u2013271|via=HathiTrust}}</ref> [[John Merven Carr\u00e8re]], a partner in the architectural firm [[Carr\u00e8re and Hastings]], said to Gilbert that \"I think it is the most successful building of its class.\"<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Irish (1985) p. 248\">{{harvnb|Irish|1985|ps=.|p=248}}</ref> [[Edwin Blashfield]], a painter, wrote a letter to Gilbert to tell him \"what a splendid impression your West Street Building makes on one, as one comes up the harbor on the way back from the other side of the Atlantic.\"<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Irish p. 396\">{{harvnb|Irish|1989|ps=.|p=396}}</ref>\n\nArchitectural critics approved of the building's design as well. An anonymous writer for the ''[[Architectural Record]]'', possibly Schuyler,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> said that he appreciated the upper stories, as well as the design of the vertical piers and the Gothic ornamentation.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=August 1907|title=The West Street Building|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=gri.ark:/13960/t3b05zj49&view=1up&seq=120|journal=Architectural Record|volume=22|pages=108|via=HathiTrust}}</ref> Another writer for the ''Architectural Record'' stated in 1909 that the structure was \"an aesthetic and technical triumph\" and \"the work of a master mind.\"<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bragdon|first=Claude|date=July 1909|title=Architecture in the United States: III. The Skyscraper|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044039466933&view=1up&seq=274|journal=Architectural Record|volume=26|pages=96|via=HathiTrust}}</ref> In 1912, a writer for the ''[[Architectural Review]]'' said that the use of ornament and the expression of the building's design \"account for the excellence of effect of the West Street Building.\"<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Swales|first=Francis S.|date=January 1912|title=The Work of Cass Gilbert|url=|journal=Architectural Review|volume=31|pages=16|via=}}</ref>\n\nPraise for the West Street Building continued even through later years, such as a 1934 article which called the structure among the city's \"most satisfying buildings.\"<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kirkham|first=Guy|date=1934|title=Cass Gilbert, Master of Style|url=|journal=Pencil Points|volume=15|pages=548|via=}}</ref> [[Ada Louise Huxtable]], speaking about a proposed Lower Manhattan development district in 1970, said that the area \"contains a few gems of substance such as Cass Gilbert's Beaux-Arts Brady Building on West Street.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Huxtable|first=Ada Louise|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/12/06/archives/an-appraisal-concept-points-to-city-of-future.html|title=An Appraisal|date=December 6, 1970|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=subscription}}</ref> [[Herbert Muschamp]] wrote in 1998 that, following the 1970s completion of the much taller World Trade Center, \"Contemporary critics evidently found it painful to praise Gilbert's West Street Building\" but that the \"wedding cake top\" of the mansard roof \"looks edible\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Muschamp|first=Herbert|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/10/09/arts/critic-s-notebook-cass-gilbert-and-the-city-eclectic.html|title=Critic's Notebook; Cass Gilbert And the City Eclectic|date=October 9, 1998|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref> The [[National Park Service]], in its 2007 historic-designation report, stated that in addition to 90 West Street's importance as one of the first skyscrapers to consistently use of Gothic detailing, the structure \"acquired additional historical importance as a witness to and survivor of the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001.\"<ref name=\"NPS p. 11\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2006|ps=.|p=11}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Architecture|New York City|NRHP}}\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Manhattan below 14th Street]]\n* [[List of New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan below 14th Street]]\n* [[Verizon Building]], another nearby building damaged in the 9/11 attacks\n\n{{-}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{Commons category|90 West Street}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Christen|first1=B.S.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x3X_D6L5JEwC&pg=PA294|title=Cass Gilbert, Life and Work: Architect of the Public Domain|last2=Flanders|first2=S.|last3=Stern|first3=R.A.M.|publisher=W.W. Norton|year=2001|isbn=978-0-393-73065-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/NARAprodstorage/lz/electronic-records/rg-079/NPS_NY/06001303.pdf|title=Historic Structures Report: West Street Building|date=December 12, 2006|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]], [[National Park Service]]|ref={{harvid|National Park Service|2006}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Irish|first=Sharon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0kKYwwEACAAJ|title=Cass Gilbert's Career in New York, 1899\u20131905|publisher=Northwestern University|year=1985|ref={{harvid|Irish|1985}}}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Irish|first=Sharon|date=April 1989|title=A 'Machine That Makes the Land Pay': The West Street Building in New York|journal=Technology and Culture|volume=30|issue=2|pages=376\u2013397|doi=10.2307/3105109|jstor=3105109|ref={{harvid|Irish|1989}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Landau|first=Sarah|title=Rise of the New York skyscraper, 1865\u20131913|publisher=Yale University Press|year=1996|isbn=978-0-300-07739-1|location=New Haven|oclc=32819286|ref={{harvid|Landau|1996}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1984.pdf|title=West Street Building|date=May 19, 1998|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York|state=collapsed}}\n{{New York City Historic Sites}}\n{{Financial District, Manhattan}}\n{{World Trade Center}}\n\n[[Category:Skyscraper office buildings in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Cass Gilbert buildings]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1907]]\n[[Category:Financial District, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:National Historic Landmarks in New York City]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:West Side Highway]]\n", "name_user": "Yoninah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDamage, renovation, and residential use", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/90_West_Street"}
{"title_page": "Deanna Barch", "text_new": "{{short description|American professor}}\n{{Notability|date=January 2020}}\n'''Deanna Marie Barch''' is a [[psychology]] professor, [[radiology]] professor and a [[psychiatry]] professor at [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University]].{{Infobox academic|citizenship=United States|workplaces=Washington University|alma_mater=Northwestern University, University of Illinois|discipline=psychology professor, radiology professor , psychiatry professor|birth_date=July 20, 1965|birth_place=St. Louis, Missouri|name=Deanna Marie Barch}}She received the APA's Distinguished Scientific Award for Early Career  for contributions to psychology in [[psychopathology]] , the [[Joseph Zubin Memorial Fund Award]], and she is also a Fellow for the [[Association for Psychological Science]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nobaproject.com/authors/deanna-m-barch|title=Deanna M. Barch|website=Noba|language=en|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>   She is a deputy editor at [[Biological Psychiatry (journal)|Biological Psychiatry]] and she was previously editor-in-chief of [[Cognitive, Affective, & Behavioral Neuroscience|Cognitive, Affective and Behavioral Neuroscience]]''.''  Barch is a member of the [[Society for Experimental Psychology and Cognitive Science|Society for Experimental Psychology]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dans.pitt.edu/deanna-barch-phd/|title=Deanna Barch, PhD {{!}} Developmental Affective Neuroscience Symposium|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBarch was born on July 20, 1965 in [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]]. Throughout 1983\u20131987, she received her B.A. in psychology from [[Northwestern University]]. During 1988-1991 and 1991\u20131993, she received her M.A. and ph,D in [[clinical psychology]] from [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]]. And throughout 1993-1994 and 1994\u20131997, she did her internship in clinical psychology, postdoctoral fellowship and NIH training fellowship from Western Psychiatric Institute and Clinic,[[University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine|University of Pittsburgh Medical School]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.wustl.edu/ccplab/people/deanna-barch/|title=Deanna Barch|date=2018-08-07|website=Cognitive Control & Psychopathology Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\nHer research includes disorders such as [[schizophrenia]], [[Depression (mood)|depression]], [[Cognitive deficit|cognitive]] and [[language deficits]]. She also focuses on [[Behavioural studies|behavioral]], [[Pharmacology|pharmacological]], and [[neuroimaging]] studies with normal and clinical populations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://source.wustl.edu/experts/deanna-barch/|title=Deanna Barch {{!}} The Source {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=The Source|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Barch collaborated with [[Alan Ceaser]]  to research about cognition in schizophrenia and core psychological and neutral mechanisms. They believe that there is a common action that will cause people to get schizophrenia. They can review the pattern of it by examining the context processing, [[working memory]] and [[episodic memory]] . <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Barch|first=Deanna M.|last2=Ceaser|first2=Alan|date=2013-12-12|title=Cognition in schizophrenia: core psychological and neural mechanisms|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1364661311002488|journal=Trends in Cognitive Sciences|language=en|volume=16|issue=1|pages=27\u201334|doi=10.1016/j.tics.2011.11.015|pmc=3860986|pmid=22169777|via=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barch, Deanna}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1960s births]]\n[[Category:American women psychologists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professor}}\n{{Notability|date=January 2020}}\n'''Deanna Marie Barch''' is a [[psychology]] professor, [[radiology]] professor and a [[psychiatry]] professor at [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University]].{{Infobox academic|citizenship=United States|workplaces=Washington University|alma_mater=Northwestern University, University of Illinois|discipline=psychology professor, radiology professor , psychiatry professor|birth_date=July 20, 1965|birth_place=St. Louis, Missouri|name=Deanna Marie Barch}}She received the APA's Distinguished Scientific Award for Early Career  for contributions to psychology in [[psychopathology]] , the [[Joseph Zubin Memorial Fund Award]], and she is also a Fellow for the [[Association for Psychological Science]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nobaproject.com/authors/deanna-m-barch|title=Deanna M. Barch|website=Noba|language=en|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>   She is a deputy editor at [[Biological Psychiatry (journal)|Biological Psychiatry]] and she was previously editor-in-chief of [[Cognitive, Affective, & Behavioral Neuroscience|Cognitive, Affective and Behavioral Neuroscience]]''.''  Barch is a member of the [[Society for Experimental Psychology and Cognitive Science|Society for Experimental Psychology]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dans.pitt.edu/deanna-barch-phd/|title=Deanna Barch, PhD {{!}} Developmental Affective Neuroscience Symposium|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBarch was born on July 20, 1965 in [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]]. Throughout 1983\u20131987, she received her B.A. in psychology from [[Northwestern University]]. During 1988-1991 and 1991\u20131993, she received her M.A. and ph,D in [[clinical psychology]] from [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]]. And throughout 1993-1994 and 1994\u20131997, she did her internship in clinical psychology, postdoctoral fellowship and NIH training fellowship from Western Psychiatric Institute and Clinic,[[University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine|University of Pittsburgh Medical School]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.wustl.edu/ccplab/people/deanna-barch/|title=Deanna Barch|date=2018-08-07|website=Cognitive Control & Psychopathology Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\nHer research includes disorders such as [[schizophrenia]], [[Depression (mood)|depression]], [[Cognitive deficit|cognitive]] and [[language deficits]]. She also focuses on [[Behavioural studies|behavioral]], [[Pharmacology|pharmacological]], and [[neuroimaging]] studies with normal and clinical populations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://source.wustl.edu/experts/deanna-barch/|title=Deanna Barch {{!}} The Source {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=The Source|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Barch collaborated with [[Alan Ceaser]]  to research about cognition in schizophrenia and core psychological and neutral mechanisms. They believe that there is a common action that will cause people to get schizophrenia. They can review the pattern of it by examining the context processing, [[working memory]] and [[episodic memory]] . <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Barch|first=Deanna M.|last2=Ceaser|first2=Alan|date=2013-12-12|title=Cognition in schizophrenia: core psychological and neural mechanisms|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1364661311002488|journal=Trends in Cognitive Sciences|language=en|volume=16|issue=1|pages=27\u201334|doi=10.1016/j.tics.2011.11.015|pmc=3860986|pmid=22169777|via=}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barch, Deanna}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1960s births]]\n[[Category:American women psychologists]]\n", "name_user": "Kj cheetham", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deanna_Barch"}
